,Not Recommended,220240,8633983,"Posted: 9 January, 2014",all,JoeBoomz,"I stuck it through to the end of the campaign, but this is the first game in a while that I was happy to delete.  This game is a “far cry” from the Trigens that I loved in the original Farcry, and it’s turned me off the series now for good.  There’s a reason why the game is so cheap.Visuals are incredible.  Sound is awesome.  The characters, voice acting, and animation are top-notch.  At its core, the FPS gameplay is superlative!  This game is BEAUTIFUL and provides movie-quality experience.  The best advice I can give if you already own it but haven’t tried it, is to play it free-form and enjoy the open-world experience.  But if you want a better FPS story experience that looks just as good, try the Crysis titles instead. As for co-op, I didn't try it, but I’m sure it’s good, as the FPS mechanics in this game are very good.However the campaign content in Farcry3 is so RAW that I cannot in good conscience recommend anyone playing this game.  I like my meat medium-rare, but this one is still on a living animal.  I am VERY concerned that underage people are experiencing it.  Now, don’t peg me off as some religious bible-thumper that is pro-censorship; you should hear me swearing and cursing at slow drivers while I tear down the roads cutting people off in my gas-guzzling tweaked-out car.  In the end, with FarCry 3, I just was not ENTERTAINED by “playing through” the actions you are required to take to progress in the game.The game is plastered with EXTREME profanity, there was no hope of me playing it with the volume up without offending anybody nearby.   The pirates are constantly swearing at you, taunting you, calling you a mutha*cker, the main character swears as he skins animals or nearly dies, and the cut scenes are so full of offensive language that it seems they had to fill a quota and fill in as many sh!t’s and fu*k’s as they could.The single-player campaign has you hunting animals (boars, pigs, deer, goats, sharks, komodo dragons, dogs, leopards, tigers, bears) with all sorts of weapons, including bows, shotguns, assault rifles, and flamethrowers.  Yes, there ACTUALLY is a mission that requires you hunt down and kill eight dogs with a flamethrower.  Now, to be fair, they were advertised as “rabid dogs that need to be put down.”  But as I approached with my flamethrower in hand, and walked right up to the pack of 8, not one attacked me.  And as I started to flame them, all they did was run away whining.  NOT a fun gaming experience.  I have a dog, she’s an important member of our family.  THIS was in no way fun.And then, the premise is, you skin each of the animals.  On the screen, as you do this, you get a gory visual of the main character inserting his knife into the dead animal, ripping the skin off, and putting the lump of flesh into his rucksack (usually with a “f*ck!” while he does it).  This is REQUIRED so that you can “craft” larger containers to carry your crap in.  Otherwise you can only carry one weapon, with little ammo, and very little money.  F@ck, if I want do that crap I will go play deer hunter.  And CRAFTING?  Why, since MineCraft came out, does everyone think they need to have it too?!   If I want to mix sh!t together, I’ll go try to cook something in the kitchen and fail miserably.  Why can’t I just pick up med kits or buy them in stores like all the other FPS games out there?  No, I have to search for green leaves to CRAFT syringes (where does the syringe come from???)Anyway, back to the story.  It is a mystical tale of human trafficking, drug trade, overcoming all odds, and saving (or betraying) your friends, who are being held hostage on the tropical paradise by pirates.  The bad guy characters are all way too over-the-top insane.  Hilarious at times, mind you, I did laugh, but Vass is simply too much, and he sure screams a lot.  Oh, and did I mention he swears?  Hoyt is a bit better for language, and funny too, but you actually see him for less of the game than Vass.You spend half of the key plot sequences in (apparently) a drug or mushroom-induced hallucinogenic state, fighting fiery demons with a bow and arrows or knives.  At the end of these sequences, I found out that, apparently, I succeeded in killing the bad guy.  What the hell?  Why can’t I just put a bullet through his head?  Oh, was that a bit too gory for mainstream gaming perhaps?At various points, the game has you holding space bar down to TORTURE people.  It includes first-person sex scenes with a crazy jungle girl.  There are themes of r@pe (including homosexual – you are asked to pucker up your a$$ up on several occasions).  There are people that are burned to death in cages in movie-like experience.  If I want to see all of that, I’ll fire up an old copy of Amistad.  This is NOT entertaining.All in all, it’s just too much.  I just want to run and gun and save the hot chick so she can suggestively tell me that I should come over later with a smile and a wink.  Happy ending.Back to the good in this sh!t sandwich – the guns are done very well, with a good selection and interesting attachment options.  The vehicles in the game are lots of fun, all sorts of road and water craft to try, albeit with some questionable physics.  The islands themselves are beautifully constructed, with beaches, caves, hidden pathways, old temples – everything you loved from Tomb Raider, and more.  The open-world concept is very nice, “freeing” the radio towers is an interesting side quest for the first 10 towers, and then it gets tedious afterwards (though the puzzle aspect of it was fun).  At least it unlocked new guns and opened up your map, otherwise I wouldn’t have bothered.  I have the same feelings about re-taking outposts, it was fun the first 20 times.  However the game requires you to do it in order to open up new “hunter quests” so that you can craft the very best equipment.By the end of my ~25-hour experience, I simply had enough and powered through the rest of the campaign so I could delete it from my hard drive.  Unfortunately for me, once I start something, I usually have to finish it.  Notice I didn’t have to mention uPlay to complain about this game.  But that part sucks too.ANYWAY, there was one memorable and awesome part of the game that I want to mention – you are required to take your newfound flamethrower and burn up some drug fields on a plantation to set back the local warlord.  As you arrive at the mission site, the soundtrack switches over to gangsta rap (a good track actually!) while you run and spray all of the drug fields.  It was very well orchestrated and reminded me of the epic fax machine scene in Office Space.  If there’s one reason I’d start up Far Cry 3 again, it would be to do that mission.  If it was available as a separate $2 mission, I’d buy it and play it.Don’t do it kids, go enjoy real life or a more encouraging game instead of wasting your time with this overly-negative story experience.EDIT:  Steam Censorship"
