,Recommended,220240,13897298,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,g4p btw,"I played this game for seventeen hours straight the first time I sat down and turned it on. I hope that convinces you that this game is great more than it convinces you that I have no self-control or sense of time. I advise anyone who is even remotely familiar with the mechanics of the Far Cry series to play on the hardest difficulty- any less and you'll probably get bored.In seventeen hours, I am not even close to done with the singleplayer story and have yet to begin playing co-op or multiplayer, but what I have seen so far is amazing. One outstanding feature is Far Cry 3's use of wildlife, which is superb, and miles ahead of its predecessor, in which you would scarecly see any animals at all. While playing this game, I am in constant fear of tigers, sharks, and crocodiles, namely, but there are other animals which range from frightening (cassowaries, they are the spawn of the devil) to irritating (herds of deer darting past). Another improvement over FC2 is the more widespread utilization of fast travel, which was a huge pain and is now endurable. I am more apprehensive about the change in how outposts are managed. Instead of having enemies respawn every time the player leaves the area, guardposts are now on by default, until permanently turned off when the player kills all the guards stationed there.tl;dr better than FC2 because of combat system, setting, plot, and ANIMALS"
