,Recommended,220240,13975475,"Posted: 13 January, 2015",all,perato,"Far Cry 3 is a solid game. I recommend it to everyone who enjoys FPS or sandbox genres. It had surprisingly well designed game play which made the game feel fresh for the whole time I played it. Graphics looked good on my 5 year old pc and sounds were even better apart from music. Voice acting was nice and sounds of the jungle felt good if not great. So it is definately a better game than FC2 or first Far cry. What surprised me most is the fact that this game really feels like both of those games thought they were nothing alike when compared to each other.Sneaking is decently done, and variety of weapons and different missions kept the game going for around 30 hours. Although the jungle looked good, it never really felt in any way threatening and was kinda like walking in a zoo or something. I hope we'll see more dense, darker and frightening jungles in the future. And more varied landscapes, these islands felt a bit too dull in a way that it all looked pretty much the same apart from some swamps. As I realised that the Island looks pretty much the same all around, I kinda stopped looking after the chests and relics. Didn't bother looking for them from the south island at all compared to the fact that around 60 % of the chests in top island was gathered and all the relics.That being said, I still didn't think this was a GOTY or even 9/10 game. I would give it 8.5/10. Main flaws of the game is the story and the characters. Story is thin and empty: about rescuing your brothers and friends and becoming a ""warrior"" for the local tribe. The story makes little sense and feels very weird time to time, especially towards the end. The atmosphere changes drastically between characters that are meant to be funny and the few minute drops of serious conversations with your friends. Combined to the fact that between missions the protagonist is running around picking flowers, hunting, flying, playing cards and doing whatever, the story feels disconnected from the world. I got the same feeling that I got from Far Cry 2; Someone wanted to make a serious game with serious plot about insanity, but at some point someone wanted to water it down and make it more relaxed and funny. The result is mish mash that's neither funny nor serious. Then again I felt that I played the game wrong. I should've just went straight for the main missions and totally ignore about everything else the environment offered me.I didn't know much about the game before I played it but I definately knew about Vaas. He was the biggest disappointment. He had maybe 10-20 mins of screen time and barely made any sense at all. And no, it's not a testimony for his insanity, it's testimony for directors lack of will to make this game a whole instead of gathering of pieces. There were no other characters that were in any way memorable, except for the main protagonist which turned out to be decent. And the ending, oh dear what the hell.All in all, I will most likely return to this game at some point, although I think I completed everything worth doing in the game, only some relics from south island and few hunting and Wanted missions got left over. Maybe I try to complete the game as fast as possible just to see if the main plot would be more coherent instead of what it turned out to be in my first play.This opinion is based on single player experience only, didn't play multiplayer or co-op."
