,Recommended,220240,10169691,"Posted: 19 May, 2014",all,Whiteswart,"There are some different angles to look at this game. It's not a brilliant, that's for sure, but I can't tell exactly, is it good or bad.Certainly, pros overcome cons, but cons aren't that small issue to negate them completely, as I do with games I'm really in love with.I start from good side: Far Cry 3 is a complete adventure at some tropical islands, where you have to (and have might to) overcome cluster♥♥♥♥, and take a life under control. Dream of so many people. Great story plot, quite comparable with Cameron's ""Avatar"" movie.As a game, first-player-view shooter with some ""gaining new abilities with experience"" (RPG-elements)... It looks good, it allows to move as you please on large and full of life archipelago, and, most needed, it allows you to shoot people (and other things) when and how you want to - which is much clever, than usual ""narrow corridor bang-bang run"" ala Call of Duty series.As an inheritor of Far Cry 2, it washed away bigger part of boredom, reason, why so many people turned predecessor down. Far Cry 3 is an open-world game, where you may actually like sub-quests and spend ""a little more"" time than you have to beat story line.But... there are cons part.First of all, oh precious realism, makers of Far Cry 3 most definetely casted it away. Some American boy found himself trigger-happy - that is one thing. But, that boy, cutting throats and sneaking to clear an avanpost silently all by himself... ""Ne veriy"" (Don't believe it) - Stanislavsky would say. Secondly, I don't like Jason Brody (protagonist) for one bit. Not a golden boy from prologue, not a rambo-like gut-cutter he evolved. All that story 'bout ""insanity"" make me sick. So, if I'd believe my ""nature instincts"", like game asks me to at start, I'd through it away. It's way Hollywood-and-plush, ""Hunger games"" on good bones of ""Battle Royale"".For game itself (gameplay process). It looks nice, but Just Cause 2 (released 3 years ago) looks greater and sharper, in terms of visual quality. As for game balance, in sandbox conditions - they have to lock key characters in buildings and scripts. Othervise, everyone will end up killed by varans and cassowary.About rambo-ing. Sure, I can silently clean an outpost, spend time to look for patrol routine, calculate lines-of-sight for every soldier on it... But why do that? Without any reconnaissance I can rush forward, and kill all of them (armed with AK's, SVD's and probably some machine-guns and RPG-7) face-to-face, with my machete and shotgun. On hardiest setting possible. On quarter or less time than silent approach. Talking 'bout realism again.Finally, for comparison with Far Cry 2, I'd say, yeah, they cut boring parts with respawnable avanposts, replace some of ""dogs of war"" realistic stuff with more hollywood-like decorations, very dramatic, of course, but edged teeth of action-stuff-fans up to zero.There are other lesser flaws, like stupid bow and driving-worse-than-in-farcry2, but I don't want to dig deeper.Overall, game is big, sometimes even fun and clever, game have catchy moments, but even then it has that ""seen it before"" scratch of second-hand cloth. Definetely NOT a must-buy. Take it at some discount, if you up to FPS games and don't fall to all that marketing crap already - or don't bother at all, it's not all that good. Total mark - 6,66/10PS: multiplayer and co-op features could have been a bigger win, but they are too glitchy, too narrow-viewed. Look at Battlefield, for much better online experience."
