,Recommended,220240,12997869,"Posted: 18 November, 2014",all,Mxthe,"I really like Far Cry 3 for the world, the gameplay mechanics and the very fun missions.Roaming around these beautiful islands is truly an amazing experience, and it often feels more like an adventure game than an action game.However Far Cry 3 has a few flaws that bothered me, for one the Dubstep music that plays during the action, was really not a good choice for the setting. Maybe it was supposed to reflect the character's youth and style, but I didn't appreciate it.And the second thing are the characters, especially Jason's friends, who I just could not believe in. Although they tried to depict human emotions, everyone's purpose really seemed to be to push the story and the events forward. The only exception being Vaas, who not only makes up for all the remaining characters, but also ends up making the game itself something unique and entertaining.The last big flaw that bugged me, were the amount of collectibles to pick up in the game. Being a completionist, I just feel compelled to go and grab the little diamond boxes that appear on my radar, but there are hundreds of them absolutely everywhere, and it ends up feeling like a really annoying grind.It's true that some of them were placed in hidden areas, which made me actually visit and explore the game, but there were simply too many in the end.Aside from those 3 little gripes I have with Far Cry 3, I absolutely loved it."
,Recommended,220240,13851420,"Posted: 5 January, 2015",all,DrProblems,"I finally bought this during the 2014 holiday sale. I'm playing the hell out of Far Cry 3 and really enjoying it, but holy♥♥♥♥♥♥ it's completely indefensible. A real shame, because the game is really fun and well designed.Problematic themes and depictions include:A raging case of Last Samurai Syndrome. A white man comes to an exotic foreign world and is quickly adopted by the oppressed natives not only into their culture but as their savior, despite the fact that he knows nothing about their environment and has no applicable skills. We're supposedly a tribe of island warriors who've been living here since time immemorial but only you can save us, scrawny Californian douchebro who's never handled a gun before!As such, the Rakyat can't do anything for themselves. Only Whitey Samurai has any kind of power in deciding how the Rakyat fight for freedom. After the heroic white boy singlehandedly liberates an enemy outpost, a half dozen Rakyat warriors show up in jeeps to secure his conquest, AK47s at the ready, but they're only there for atmosphere. They're unable to take outposts themselves or even help the hero out. I know that having the player be the only being in the world with agency is a convention of open world games going back farther than GTA, but it's pretty ♥♥♥♥ed that these people literally have to wait around for the white hero to save them.Citra. The spiritual leader of the Rakyat is a colonial fantasy straight out of Victorian pulp fiction, the hypersexual female native drawn to the white savior, despite being surrounded at all times by hunky warriors from her own culture. Weirdly, she doesn't even look like she's the same ethnicity as the other Rakyat, who are supposedly... Polynesian? (The game never says exactly where Rook Island is.) Citra is ethnically unplaceable, and definitely has more ""caucasian"" features than the rest of her people, presumably to maximize her sexual appeal to the game's target demographic. Also, the warrior initiation ceremony of the Rakyat involves Citra straddling you while topless and grinding on your junk. Whoops, that was a spoiler, sorry.Dennis. At the beginning of the story, the white hero is rescued and guided by a magical negro witch doctor. Dennis has been adopted by the Rakyat years before, but is not worthy to be their savior himself. He can only assist our white hero, despite being depicted as much more competent and experienced.There are two enemy factions, the savage bloodthirsty ""Pirates"" and the professional mercenary ""Privateers"". The disorganized and drug-addled Pirates are all Afro-Caribbean, while the much more competent Privateers are (mostly white) Americans.The main bad guy is a white South African who is of course depicted as a genocidal monster. Poor Afrikaners, no other ethnic group is so easy to demonize in video games and action movies. It's not their fault that their accent makes them all sound like Bond villains.In conclusion, buy it cheap during a Steam sale, enjoy exploring the gorgeous world, the awesome stealth killing mechanics, and the wide variety of customizable guns, and shake your head at the tone-deaf racism."
