,Recommended,220240,13282629,"Posted: 8 December, 2014",all,Contron,"Far Cry 3 is a mixed bag. I've enjoyed it thoroughly, but it seems to be one of those games which provides a lot of things to the player, but doesn't do any of them particularly well. I bought the deluxe edition version of this game for £5, so I'll happily admit that it's a steal; I do think it's been worth my money, however.Good pointsThe AI is much better than in Far Cry 2 - multiple playstyles are actually an option now, rather than being forced to go rambo for each of the outposts in the previous gameGraphical-wise, it is a very pretty looking game. The forests look quite lush and the upgrades to the engine help compliment this, even if the ambient occlusion seems pretty strong at timesThere is actually a story that you can follow this time. To me, Far Cry 2's story seemed pretty nonexistent, so this is a large improvementA much wider diversity of weapons compared to its predecessor, and the attachments and paintjobs let you customise firearms to suit your styleMuch of the bad points in Far Cry 2 have been addressed and built upon, for instance outposts respawning if you venture a couple of meters away and the driving physics is much betterBad pointsThere's only one environment in the game, and it's the jungle. I understand this was remedied in Far Cry 4, but it does make it slightly dull when the entirety of both islands are the sameOnce you've completed the game, there isn't much to do other than free the remaining outposts and complete the side quests - which personally, aren't that interestingOverall, I'd recommend you purchase this, but I'd wait until it's next on sale."
