,Recommended,220240,22146831,"Posted: 30 March, 2016",all,JacquesLeSauve,"The Far Cry games are very much the Final Fantasy of first-person shooters - each game within these series plays very similarly but are almost completely unconnected to one another, they've both spawned multiple sequels and broken out into spin-offs, and you're unlikely to find a universal answer when asking which game is everyone's favourite. I basically like this entry in the series, but for all its efforts, it still falls far short in taking the throne as best of the Far Cry games.Here you'll play as Jason Brody, an adventuring party dude turned captive turned escapee turned murdering, rampaging sociopath who slaughters his way across a couple of islands as he rescues his friends and overthrows a villainous regime. It's the feel-good story of the year! By which I mean it's total, utter toss. It could have been a typical, lazy, straightforward story about finding the bad guy and getting the girl then living happily ever after, but almost counterintuitively, the fact that they tried to do something more with it actually only made it worse than if they hadn't tried at all. The problem is the writing. It's f*cking awful. Painfully so. Between the dialogue, characters and their actions, even the goddamn journal entries, every instance only serves to grate against the player rather than ingratiate you into the world. I honestly struggle to think of a single likable character in the game. From the island's inhabitants to the ""helpful"" NPCs to your best friends and even the very guy you play as, pretty much every single human being in this game is an *sshole. Like, a massive one. The kind that smells really bad and is surrounded by thick, curly hairs and has little speckles of brown all around it. Everyone around you is either going to be trying to kill you, will betray you, or mean well but only be an annoying c*ck instead. Ev-er-y-one!The main antagonists of the story are Vaas, a deeply unhinged leader of a large and merciless band of pirates, and his boss, Hoyt, the equally deranged slave trader and mastermind behind all the brutality being forced upon the islands he has taken over. The developer seems to have taken great inspiration from Heath Ledger's Joker and try to make these characters deep and complex threats who toy with their victims, but I never really felt it. My problem with it is the fact there are so few interactions with these people, they're really talked about more than they're actually seen. And when we do see them, pretty much every interaction with them comes in the form of a cutscene rather than any kind of meaningful gameplay. This really diminished their intimidation for me. Like... we almost had to take the game's word that they were vile, evil people since we didn't get to see any real examples of that. Had Vaas been given an opportunity to be a bad*ss and we could have seen him leading an insane, nihilistic charge into some enemy forces and win, or if we'd fought him several times, maybe then I could have bought it. But, instead, the greatest threat from him is that he might bore you to death as he talks and yells his way through a handful of cutscenes at you. It just didn't work for me. I mean, I've ripped men's throats out with my knife, set dozens on fire with flamethrowers and Molotovs, and massacred countless men and animals with a huge array of weapons and vehicles. Believe me, Vaas is not the worst example of humanity in this game. Granted, Hoyt is given a little more presence and chances to be villainous, but it still doesn't leave much impact. But you'll be pleased to know there is some gameplay here, which is far more successful at gripping the player.It's an open world, first-person shooter, so you pretty much already know the score by now. Buy, find or earn some weapons, customise them as you see fit, then use them to kill, kill, kill your way through a few dozen hour's worth of missions and exploration. There are basically three different things you can choose to pursue to pass the time in this game, either run around searching for a dizzying wealth of largely meaningless collectibles (this is a Ubisoft game, after all), clear out enemy outposts which reduce hostile presence in the immediate area, or just play through the story missions and see where those take you. The story stuff is OK, I guess. Go to location A, kill target X or destroy objective Y, then get away to safety. Either that or go on a handful of drug trips as you ""discover yourself"" and unlock the warrior within. I found these sequences to be pretty slow and plodding, though, or just a chore to play through. But maybe that's just me and others will enjoy some of the more abstract visuals and break from the more standard killing simulator the rest of the missions are.I think most will agree, though, that the real fun to be had here is in the outposts. These are camps scattered all throughout the islands and guarded by several enemies which vary type from outpost to outpost. Most will have basic grunts patrolling, while others may have snipers keeping watch or flamers stomping around the grounds or dogs sniffing you out. How you approach these is entirely up to you. If you want to rock up with a grenade launcher and crater the place, go for it. Maybe you want to try incinerating the camp and picking off the stragglers amid all the panic and confusion. Handy with a silenced sniper rifle? Go pop some heads, son. Or perhaps you're the kind of tasty b*stard that likes to sneak into the heart of the lair and knife everyone in the back one by one without anyone ever knowing what hit them. It's yours for the taking, however you want to take it. It does pay to be sneaky, as liberating an outpost without being discovered will net you 1500 XP, while simply taking it by brute force will only earn you 500. But there's really no shortage of XP being handed out in the game (I maxed out mine and unlocked every ability long before the end of the game), so you shouldn't worry about that too much.There are some online options, too, like PvP multiplayer or some specially made co-op missions, but, yeah... just do yourself a favour and don't bother with them. I only played an hour or two of the multiplayer, and really tried getting into it, but it's nothing special. And the co-op missions are a bloody mess. They're little more than going to an area and holding it down and fending off waves of spawning enemies until the game decides to let you move on to the next location and do it again. It would be a passable distraction were it not so riddled with bugs (that on several occasions made it impossible for me to continue) or lousy matchmaking or options in general. I wouldn't dare to call them lazy, but I would say they feel tacked on, like they were made at a time when they felt they needed to have these features as a bullet point on the back of the box to sell copies and make people feel like they'd gotten their money's worth and not sell their discs after tha main campaign. But there's no shortage of online FPSs to play, either competitively or cooperatively, and unless you had no other option, I don't know why you'd stick with this. Though, that said, some people are, as the games still seemed to be very active and populated with plenty of players. F*ck knows why.While, yes, I do pretty much recommend this, at the same time, as seems to be the increasing trend with Ubi games, they've taken 10 or 15 hour's worth of a good, fun idea, then stretched it out to dozens of hours, where every hour stretched beyond its point starts to wear you down rather than entertain, and TONS of niggling interface issues and bugs and crashes keep kicking you down. But in certain doses, spread over a large period of time, this is a fun, solid shooter. Though, for my money, FC2 is still the peak of the series and a better place to get your shooty, stabby kicks."
