,Recommended,220240,11299436,"Posted: 17 July, 2014",all,Porkchop,"When Far Cry 2 released not many great titles were out at the time, at least for consoles. (It was one of the first games having trophies on PS3.) I remember many of my friends buying it and not liking it, but for me Far Cry 2 quickly emerged as a special title that I will soon not forget. Probably one of the most balanced games I've played online.Far Cry 3 is a more fluid version, with more sidequests. One of the first things that hits you is how it emerges you in a exotic and this time tropical world. Visually a fantastic looking game. The guns feel powerful and sound and feel different from one another. It's unforuntate that one needs to use Uplay to play it, an annoyance, but to me ""oh well"" (and I despise Origin and will never install it). The story is inconsistent, not making sense at times, definitely more towards the end. However, compared to recent blockbuster hits its decent yet not believable. Jason Brody develops into a lame hipster, who quickly learns Rambo-like skills - it was a little too fast and like I said not believable to me. I think that's beside the point though, as Far Cry 3 really shines in moments where the player can move from a silent, stealthy, and slow approach to a fast-gunning and fast-paced gameplay. For example, when you want to snipe everyone in an encampment, get spotted, then blast everyone away with a LMG. Setting up IEDs on enemy roads or throwing molotovs into the jungle and setting everything ablaze are definitely setting you up for gaming moments that are unmatched. I think many people are going to hit their screenshot button. Overall, Far Cry 3 is a great game and it doesn't surprise that many are excited for its next installment (albeit releasing quite early after its announcement)."
,Recommended,220240,11074032,"Posted: 4 July, 2014",all,Tiagozak,"Far Cry 3 is a game that made quite a stir back in 2012, when it was launched. It won multiple Game of the Year awards, and was considered by many one of the best FPS ever, and some few selected ones even said it was the best FPS ever. I bought it at the last summer sale by 4,99€, and had my expectations high. After a full 13-hours playthrough, in which I've made the main missions and one of each activities to really know how everything is, I must admit that I was dissapointed. I will divide this review in some aspects and rate them, in order to do a fairly imparcial, honest review about this apparently revolucionary game.Graphics: probably the biggest asset of the game. Beautiful graphics that take computers to their limit (I imagine how the consoles should run this game) and give a good immersion feeling. Gorgeous views, variety of fauna and flora, good character models and some very nice effects. While one may note some recycling of scenarios, and some lazyness in some areas (which makes exploration sometimes tedious, boring and repetitive), the islands are fairly well designed and concieved. 90/100.Gameplay: one thing said about Far Cry 3 was the innovative gameplay. I must disagree. FC3's gameplay it's like an improved version of FC2's gameplay. With some dumbing down in the middle, and some rather useless features, the gameplay adds some nice features that make it a fairly singular game. The feeling of dejà-vú is present, but, since it's an huge improvement of FC2's already flawless gameplay, it's almost perfect. The only problem, as said, it's the little dumbing down of some features and the lack of some obvious ones (like firing weapons while driving). 95/100.Sound: I must admit that I don't really pay much attention to a game's soundtrack. Without much information, but with some reconsideration, I found that the sound gives support to the game. There isn't nothing remarkable, but it's made with quality. The voice acting is perfect, the sound of the weapons are brutal and realistic and all those little details make the sound as good as the game. Still, it has nothing really special or memorable. 89/100.Story/Plot: the plot may be defined in one word: horrible. You are Jason Brody, a spoiled guy that looks more like a wimpy child, that goes together with is brothers, friends and girlfriends to a trip to a archipelago fo tropical islands. The trip goes bad: after a skydiving experience, they are all captured by a local group of pirates/guerrilla, led by the maniac Vaas Montenegro. Jason manages to escape and allies himself with the Rakyat, a local tribe led by Citra, Vaas' sister, in order to rescue his friends. Vaas was one of the most hype-giving characters in the last few years and was the main reason that made people buy this game, but it was just a marketing putsch. Vaas rarely appears and it's not really that interesting. It's a wasted character used to sell the game. The main villain isn't really Vaas, it's another character that proves himself to be more interesting than Vaas. Jason goes form a big ♥♥♥♥♥, spoiled guy to a mighty warrior that has sex with Citra just because they had to put boobs in the game, just because it's what sells. The whole process of going from city boy to jungle warrior is unnatural, badly performed and with many flaws. He is captured and executed multiple times, and yet survives them all, like if multiple miracles had happened. I could really get into more absurds and bad plot decisions, but I won't. Only the second part          of the game really delivers a more solid story (it's a part where you actually fight the real villain instead of the pawn Vaas). At least it allowed more unique, variated missions, which is very positive and really complements the gameplay. It has some good moments, but globally, it's bad. 65/100.Other aspects and final score: the game, a being open world, sandbox like experience, offers many activities in the 2 islands you can explore, such as hunting, takeovers, exploring, etc. The longevity is quite good for an FPS, but I doubt it reaches more than 30 hours. The Uplay thing is quite dull, and it would only profit from Steamworks. I have not tried the multiplayer because I don't actually care about it, but from what I hear, it's acceptable. I have not played many games from 2012 (probably I haven't played any), but I can assure that this is probably one of the best. With other strong candidates, like Borderlands 2 and Dishonored, which I haven't played, I think the fight for the title of GOTY 2012 would be fierce and tough. The final score, based on the average between the 4 scores I gave above and a factor of correction based on the other aspects, is of 86 out of 100. While it was a desilusion, it's still strongly reccomended."
