,Recommended,220240,9439184,"Posted: 12 March, 2014",all,CorvusCorax,"Far Cry 3, for me, is what Far Cry 2 should have been. In its predecessor the game lacked a proper story and also the game was very difficult. I remember the creators explaining it with the story, i.e. in order to really grasp the reality of the harsh African environment the game had to be hard even on a normal difficulty level.Far Cry 3 finally has a story and a more interesting protagonist. Also, the antagonist is memorable - his attitude, the voice acting, everything related to his personality stands out. The game gradually gets more difficult and you have a sense of progress here - there are no respawning enemies at the outposts any more: once you capture an outpost the local natives will take full control over it. They later on send patrols to further explore the island so it is now common to see them fighting with the enemies. I liked this approach as you could truly feel you were part of a story here and the fate of an entire people was dependent upon you. Oh, you want to clear an outpost in a much better way? (e.g. following the stealth approach) No worries, the game lets you reset all outposts so that you can complete these again earning some extra achievements.Proper fauna was also missing in the predecessor. Here you have all kinds of animals you can hunt. Hunting is important as by obtaining the skin / hide of your prey you can apply upgrades to your gear. You can have greater pouches to have more money with you or store more ammunition. I liked how you can even pick up herbs so that you can craft syringes that grant you an extra ability for a short period of time to make battles easier.And of course we have an enormous amount of collectible items scattered throughout the island. They are atop mountains or deep within in hidden caves. You need to swim in from the outside only to suddenly be attacked by a crocodile.Far Cry 3 is an exceptionally good game. If you don't mind signing up for UPlay (achievements are logged via that instead of Steam) you should not have a problem with this game. It is beautiful, it is entertaining, it has a good story and an amazing wildlife (e.g. a tiger can easily attack a deer in front of your eyes). And what's more in order to gather all collectibles and complete all side missions the game will hold you captive for at least 50 hours. And this is only the single player campaign as you still have coop mission and multiplayer."
