,Recommended,220240,8825259,"Posted: 23 January, 2014",all,Formologic23,"I didn't have high expectations of FarCry 3 after playing FarCry 2, and FarCry 1's story was a little far fetched for me. I was immediately engaged by the opening scene of FarCry3 and I had to play it a couple of times because of how the save points work. I was mostly engaged by the story, although there are some points you want to go WTF? But there is a really cool scene that blew my mind. While shooting bad guys is pretty repetitive, I had a lot of fun capturing Radio Towers and Bandit camps for the challenge of not being detected. I didn't spend a whole lot of time searching for relics or loot because it would never end, but the game is just gorgeous.The ""upgrades"" you can do to yourself are fun and add to the game and most of them I didn't find useless. Another nice feature about the game is the ending. Once you beat the game, you have the option to ""leave"" or continue on. I opted for continuing on, but all I have left is searching for relics, and there is about 300 in the game. Not really worth the time to me. I don't know about the replayability of the game, but it was worth the discount I paid for it. It's one of three or four games out of 90 or so that I've actually wanted to complete.I would recommend this game, even at the current regular price, but if you can find it on a discount, even better. I do have one complaint. I would consider my computer hardware to be above the norm, but the game sometimes would run great and then go down to 10 or so FPS, which when doing certain tasks (radio tower medical quests), it would make it extremely challenging. You may find other reviews complaining about how the game is not optimized, and I felt the same pain. Didn't detract from the game, but out of 5 stars, I would give it a 4.5 for this reason. If it ran well 100% of the time, I would have given it a 5."
