76561198055709921,Recommended,220240,8554055,"Posted: 4 January, 2014",all,Dadelus,"This may be long, but there are some things about this game that should be known before someone buys it.  I have no idea why the review says I played it for 1 hour or so as I completed the game and it certainly didn't take an hour.  Thanks UPlay and Steam for their accuracy and well done programs.The game is actually very, very good for the most part.  It is interesting and very fun to play with some reasonable challenges for an FPS and has some nice RPG elements thrown in to make it a bit more interesting.  The graphics are pretty good.  The NPC AI was actually good for the animals but I am not sure why people (NPCs) were added.  For example, I found a woman crying on the beach and some guy carrying a piece of ""I"" beam on a road while exploring.  There was no way to interact with them - even just to say ""hi"" let alone what they were doing or if I could help.  It just seemed sort of stupid to have them in the game if they did nor added nothing to the game.  I also wondered why there were groups of the locals standing in locations just shooting guns in the air.  I typically went towards any gun fire I heard, hoping for a nice fight and earning some skill points, but typically found 3 NPCs shooting guns in the air for no reason and no way to find out why.Weapons were not over or under powered and accuracy was pretty darn good as I was doing lots of headshots with various weapons from a pretty good distance.For a FPS, the story wasn't bad, a nice and simple ""go kill the bad guys"" like it should be - but for the minor RPG aspects it was terrible; clichéd, contrived completely uninteresting and didn't add anything to the game that the simple ""go kill the bad guys"" didn't already set as a completely adequate game story.For the most part, the game is quite good and it is well worth buying and playing if you get it on sale for a low, low cost, but I wouldn't pay more than $10.00 for this game - and here's why.  The designers and programmers were lazy or stupid or just didn't care about elements and the game.Walking along and getting stuck on a slight protrusion on the ground is just bad, lazy programming. I constantly hit this glitch entering the village store and on bridges, stairs, in buildings and caves, etc.  It was just annoying and completely distracting when focused in a fire fight and sneaking/running for cover and getting stuck on a door transom 1/2 inch high or getting stuck on a stone path in a cave while trying to skirt some hazard or manoeuvring to figure out how to get over/around some obstacle.  Same with looting a body or chest - if you are not in the exact, correct spot, you have to adjust left-right-back-forward until you hit the sweet spot to get the signal you can now loot, empty, skin or gather the item in front of you.The game is advertised as ""open world"" - it lied.  It isn't open and I constantly ran into a big warning that flashed on the screen that I was leaving the mission area and unless I got back, the mission would fail.  It actually was so linear in places it ruined play.  I want to get to that rock to use my sniper rifle and get a tactical advantage, but I'm 10 feet off the path the game insists I follow so I fail the mission?  Not open world by any definition. Yeah, doing nothing but wandering and exploring is open world, but then it doesn't matter.Cut scenes.  Other than the first conversation cut scene, none of the others actually added anything to the story, didn't aid in doing anything and were just annoying and frustrating and had enough sway and jerk and tilt to make you seasick.  Did I really need to know that some native was in the USA as a mechanic and got made fun of because of his accent?  I'm not sure what this added or why it was in the game.Then there was the times you are getting really involved and things were getting really interesting and... the game takes control of your character, then you have control, then the game, then you, then a big white flash and a fade out and you wake up to a cut scene with your character moaning and groaning and gasping for 2-3 minutes and suddenly with a bright white flash you are back in the game.  It was frustrating, stupid and annoying and ruined some of the best parts of the game. Worse, in some cut scenes the way to get through was by button mashing. Really?  I am fighting some NPC/animal and I have to press ""E"", ""C"", ""mash Space"", ""Left Mouse"", ""Right Mouse"" then ""mash A, A, A"" when cued by a big flashing symbol on the screen to successfully win? I missed everything on the screen because I was watching for the cues on what button to mash.  Annoying and stupid.The Boss fights are incredibly stupid, lame and so wasteful.  You spend time and effort and actually have a ton of fun doing any number of things in the game to build up your character and get skills and abilities and weapons and when you are all prepared for the big Boss fight.... none of it matters.  The stereotyped, native witch with the terrible accent (and she is the ugliest female I have ever seen in a game - and that includes 8-bit games I played years ago) puts you on LSD or some jungle juice drink and you wander through a haze to kill a smoke monster (the easiest Boss I have ever fought-3 arrows to the face and - done) and then you have to stab another stereotyped native with a bad accent holding a magic knife.  No skills needed nor any abilities, just run up to him until the cut scene takes over and you stab him and he dies.  Gee, thanks for making what should be the best and most challenging part of the game just a lame, stupid cut scene.Do I recommend the game?  Yes, but if you get it for a really low cost and can take the frustrating and poorly done parts in stride.  About 2/3 of the game is hugely fun and offers hours of interesting entertainment fighting, looting, exploring and collecting certain items, so again, I'd buy it if it's less than $10.00."
