76561197970530678,Recommended,220240,8914644,"Posted: 30 January, 2014",all,Argh!,"Far Cry 3 is a brilliantly executed open-world First Person Adventure. Many call this an FPS, but that’s only a small facet of this game. I enjoyed the first half of the game, but I had to will myself to cross the finish line.  FC3 has many “tacked-on” elements that don’t really add to the experience. It has “crafting” and a “skill tree” that could have easily been absorbed in to the games progression, as neither really changes your game experience beyond expanding your inventory capacity or adding a new way to take out enemies. A decent player will have both maxed out well before the end-game.The weapon progression was fun; especially the high powered weapons that send enemies flying on impact. The addition of weapon mods was nice, but arbitrary. The mods were only available on the higher tiers of weapons, and limited to an artificial cap. The mod categories are suppression, magazine size, and optics (in some cases you could stack optic choices, like adding night vision to a long range scope); unfortunately the designers chose to artificially limit the number of attachments and only allow them on top tier weapons. The result is a huge number of underused weapons. I might have experimented with more of the lower tier weapons if they were upgradable. This would not have thrown off balance since there was so much redundancy in weapon choices anyway.The story starts with strong conflict which cements you in to the mythos quickly. I enjoy hardboiled tales as much as the next guy, but there was very little foil to the darkness  and grittyness. For a 40+ hour experience, it would have been nice to have some humor and light hearted content mixed in to the hard hitting main quest. There were some likeable characters along the way – Vass was a good “bad-guy”, Sam was a lot of fun, and the deep cover agent straight out of Miami Vice was a nice touch, but I found I was less interested in the main story and more interested in my own exploration. The number of times I got shot, stabbed, drowned, and “left for dead” started to become an in-joke (they even mention it in the game).Overall I would lump this game in to the same family as Skyrim or Fallout 3, both of which far eclipse this game in story and progression. The area that Far Cry shines is in the gameplay mechanics, and the interaction with the world. I felt much more in control of my characters physicality which ultimately sustained my intrest allowing me to play through to the end. (The wingsuit is AWESOME!) I really did get the feeling of being a one-man-army action-hero without it feeling like I was dealing with idiotic AI. It’s worth playing and I look forward to seeing how they improve this franchise going forward."
