,Recommended,220240,11202594,"Posted: 12 July, 2014",all,doomed,"If you like FPS games, you're going to love this.Don't let the open-world intimidate you, the story line is in fact big, but structured enough so you dont get lost.The game map (the islands) is super huge with a lot of sidequests. There will be exploration, meaning running and driving through the wilderness, looking for animals to skin, plants to craft syringes (they act as powerups) and other items to collect. This does consume a lot of time.There's a vast realistic arsenal in the game, but it takes time to have them all available. So in the beginning you might feel kinda weak but keep on! My best suggestion is to unlock the radio towers first, they bring map visibility and immediate weapon unlocks on the town shops.Visuals are awesome, really beautiful, and the controls are good (I wish there was more keyboard shortcuts though).Menus and options are well organized and presented. This game is technically perfect.Enjoy."
,Not Recommended,220240,11202008,"Posted: 12 July, 2014",all,The Good Sir Hatter,"Considering this game was hyped to all hell, I figured that I would at least kind of enjoy the experience. And to an extent, I did, but some horribly glaring issues with the game just ruined it all for me.Now the first thing I want to note before I go into any of this is that I played through Far Cry 3: Blood Dragon before this, and I loved the experience. That game was silly and marvelous, and I would recommend it in a heartbeat. This game, however, manages to be worse than the game that was done on a significantly lower budget running on the same engine. Here's why:First, the mission design is repetitive as all hell. For the most part your missions boil down to ""Go into restricted zone X to find/kill/blow up Y and then leave restricted zone X"". Practically every story mission is like this. And practically every side mission is like this as well, even the hunting missions. It turned into kind of a chore to do everything, and that's bad. It worked better in Blood Dragon because even though it had the same problem, it was on a much, MUCH smaller scale. You were a badass supersoldier who could zoom over to your objective in less than 10 seconds and it'd be done even faster. In Far Cry 3 it takes more time to get where you're going, and then more time to do what you're doing, which makes what used to be a niggling complaint a gigantic complaint.Second, too many turret sections. I should not have to explain this, but I will: game developers and designers, nobody wants to sit in the same spot holding down LMB for fifteen minutes while you scroll a background for us. It's not fun, it's not satisfying, it's boring, and it's tedious, and Far Cry 3 has turret sections out the♥♥♥♥♥ This is a crime against game design, and whoever's smart idea this was should be hanged upside down by their pinkie toes for even suggesting it.Third, crafting and RPG elements are super underutilized and feel utterly tacked on. If you're going to put crafting or RPG mechanics into your game, make it INTERESTING. Make it so you have to actually BUILD A CHARACTER, so you actually have to DISCOVER IMPORTANT CRAFTING RECIPES, not this. Far Cry 3's leveling system comes down to this: kill everyone in sight until you ding, get the next linear upgrade, rinse, lather, repeat. The skills you perk into hardly ever have an effect on gameplay, and when they do, all they are is another canned animation for your takedown that is hardly ever useful. I never used the grenade takedown, I never used the hanging takedown, I hardly used the double takedown, when I did it wasn't useful, I didn't use the chained takedown, I didn't use the knife takedown, and I didn't use the gun takedown. All I used were the vanilla takedown, the heavy takedown (which is just the vanilla takedown on big enemies), and the death from above takedown. Everything else was stupid and pointless. And the other skills were dumb things like ""Reload faster"" or ""Get more money from looting"" or ""Reload when aimed down sights"".Part deux of point three, the crafting is terrible. All you do is farm out animals to get bigger bags and then just get all the green plants for nonstop healing items. There is no reason to get anything except green plants after you acquire all the bag upgrades, and it could have been used for something interesting. Let me make special weapons, or traps, let me use all this stuff, let me fashion some jerryrigged armor SOMETHING, ANYTHING. Instead it's ""Got all the bags? Okay now all the animals are walking money go nuts."" Horrible crafting system, they should have just left it out altogether.And finally, the story is just absolutely pathetic. Now, before you jump down my throat about it let me make this perfectly clear: I loved Vaas and Hoyt. They were excellently written characters. Unfortunately, this game does not star either one of those characters, it stars Jason Brody, a moron who claims to have never shot a gun, yet guns down armies of pirates and privateers like he's been doing it since he came out of the womb, and is ""super serious"" about saving his friends, but can't keep himself from making stupid pop culture references every thirty seconds. This character ruined literally the entire story. The game can't decide if it wants to be silly or serious, so it tries to do both and it fails utterly. The ludonarrative dissonance in this game is just insane levels of bad, and you just want to murder Jason by the end of it all. I'll go so far as to say that this is probably the worst story I've seen in a game, not because the concept of the story is bad, but because the execution is just awful.All in all, I would say skip this game and just get Blood Dragon. Blood Dragon doesn't have any of these problems, even the turret sections are more toned down, and frankly they're actually well executed. Blood Dragon succeeds in everything Far Cry 3 fails in and more, and it's cheaper as well. So, yeah, just get Blood Dragon. Just get Blood Dragon. What I'm saying is buy Blood Dragon."
76561198049124398,Recommended,220240,11226135,"Posted: 13 July, 2014",all,Red Marlin,"The first half of this game is a masterpiece.  The second half is terrible.  But overall, I am very glad I got it, and I will always remember it.The first half of the game has very enjoyable gameplay, and I like that you can choose whether you want to be stealthy or just go full-on Rambo with guns ablaze.  Taking over strongholds were definitely the best part of the game for this reason - it's you, a bunch of bad guys, and it's all up to you how you deal with it.The missions throw this tactic out the window.  For the first half of the game, you are pretty much forced to use stealth tactics, and for the second half, it's basically Call of Duty type shooting.  Speaking of which...The second half of the game throws all tactics out the window, and in my opinion, it was thoroughly unenjoyable.  Whereas with any other part of the game, you can approach the enemies however you want, in several of the missions in the second half, they don't even spawn until you are about ten feet away, meaning if you were relying on the bow or the sniper (like I was), tough luck ya ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥.  If you insist upon playing the second part of the game, my advice would be to carry: a large machine gun, a shotgun, a rocket launcher, and one type of long range weapon.  Stealth matters no more.Obviously, Vaas is the best character in the game.  But after he's gone (don't think I'm spoiling anything there), the game just felt empty - you're only halfway done after that point, and Hoyt is not the same, not by a long shot.  I kept playing just to see the ending that everyone was talking about, and even that was pretty disappointing.So to sum it up: if you get this game, my advice would be to play the first half of the game and enjoy it to its fullest, then either go full-on sandbox and forget the story or drop the game altogether and just watch the ending on Youtube.  You're missing nothing between the two."
