,Not Recommended,220240,8627953,"Posted: 8 January, 2014",all,Araganor,"Far Cry 3 is a great game that showcases how far video games have come as far as technology goes, but I personally found it uninteresting and unoriginal. It's a great game in its own right, but in my opinion it does little to separate itself from other shooters except being open world, which is not enough to keep my interest.Don't get me wrong. This is a gorgeous game, with a carefully crafted world, decent storyline, and about everything else you can expect from a triple-A title. The way the game tries to ""innovate"" is through the addition of RPG-like elements, such as crafting (a process created to encourage players to go out and hunt wild animals or collect random flowers of different colors), stealth (very similar system to any Bethesda game, crouch and hope they don't see you), and skill trees. However, many of these mechanics simply served to irritate me, in a way that is hard to explain unless you have played the game yourself.In my experience, crafting simply made gameplay tedious for me. I would often find far too many of one kind of plant or creature, but hardly any of another. My inventory quickly became overloaded, yet I hadn't found a single hide of the required type to craft a larger bag with more inventory space. It felt more like a barrier to the gameplay, creating unneeded tasks to fill up gameplay time rather than making the actual experience more interesting.Stealth (something I am very fond of in my action games) was hampered by the fact that once you silently kill someone, the body becomes unmovable, alerting enemies who discover it to your presence. I later discovered through the internet that there is a perk that allows you to move bodies, but only if you hold down a key as you are killing the enemy, with the corpse becoming once again unmovable after you drop it.Another thing that bothered me was my inability to ""click"" with the main character or put myself in his shoes. He (I don't even remember his name) seems like a normal guy, thrown into a situation that is way over his head. I understand that much. What I don't understand that breaks the experience for me is how he suddenly becomes a superhuman army of one, who can suddenly sprint for hours across a jungle, getting shot 5 times, while raining a firey bullet hell on his enemies, but sounding like a whiny kid in all of the cutscenes (ALL OF THEM). He is potrayed as young man, but it feels like he is still in high school. When the player is put in control of him he is suddenly an action hero, complete with sunglasses. I don't buy the ""tatoo gives me strength"" crap either, because one would hope his voice would be a little less high-pitched if it did. The development team tries to make the hero relateable to by making him seem inexperienced with death (Illustrated in the beginning of the game whenhis brother kills the guard, and then when the antagonist kills his brother) but then suddenly turns him into a f*cking death-dealing grim reaper of AK-47's with no explanation. (hormones?)Ubisoft's mandatory Uplay account is also tiresome, forcing you to create yet another email-linked account that allows corporate bodies to send you unwanted spam.If you enjoy high quality first person shooters but don't care about orginality, then your money is well spent. Far Cry 3 is a very well made game, in a perfect position to show off the revolutions in video game techonology. Don't let me stop you from getting the game, which is worth the money development-wise. However, if you came here looking for innovation or something new, keep looking."
