,Recommended,220240,2868693,"Posted: 6 January, 2013",all,Hank,"8/10 *Warning  Some Spoilers Below*Far Cry 3 is a great game, hell it's excellent but it's not without it's flaws (and I'm no IGN to willy nilly throw 10/10's or 9/10's around. The game looks, feels and plays very fluidly. The story is very solid for the most part displaying Jason's trasition into almost madness as he becomes a completely different person while on Rook Island.Vaas is probably one of the greatest antagonists or just characters in a video game, up there with the Mark Hamill as the Joker in Arkham Asylum. Using stealth to take out an entire outpost of pirates feels (and is) very rewarding. Incorporating hunting wild animals into gameplay to create new gear is great. Surveying and sniping off targets is incredibly fun just as running in guns a blazing with a flamethrower or LMG.Enemy NPC's can spot you from miles away sometimes which is frustrating but generally it makes sense when you're out in the open (though sometimes you're well hidden on higher ground or in trees etc). The characters in the game as a whole are really well written, voiced and mo-capped. They look and sound like real people and are believeable.Some bad points that prevent the game from being a 9 or more out of 10 are. Imo the story drops off in quality 3/4 of the way through becoming quite predicatable. The main down fall of the game is that it's pretty short (~10hrs actual story) and there's little to do once you've completed the main story. Luckily (most of) the story is of very high quality and does make up for this a little. The side missions or activities are pretty bland. I don't want to go racing round the island, it's fine ad lib  but I'm not playing Far Cry for racing. Why not have an activity where you get to use the  Wing suit or Parachute for an attack of a outpost or just time trials etc. Apparently all native residents of Rook Island are New Zealanders and speak and look like Maori's. NPC's other than main characters in missions have limited dialogue and have little effort put into their movements/humanity it makes the huge effort into the story characters seem out of place. Some video game logic is present here too, a guy from a circle of rich kids is able to fire and maintain a large range of different pistols/rifles/LMG's/an rpg/flamethrower/Composite bow and more. Apart from Liza commenting that now he's ""running around loaded with guns"" no one seems to find his new found expertise strange."
