,Recommended,220240,10512727,"Posted: 18 June, 2014",all,dec0d3d,citra bOObs x)))10/10
,Recommended,220240,3262246,"Posted: 5 December, 2012",all,jc helmet,"It's time for a super serious review guysA Herd of Cassowaries rampaging through a pirate outpost. Sneaking through the jungle until a tiger decides to try to make you its lunch. Ramming a car bomb into a base and setting it off. A hot pink 1911.If any of those sounded appealing, then you’ll probably like Far Cry 3. To put it simply, Far Cry 3 is what Far Cry 2 should have been. Almost every aspect of it is improved. No more are there infinitely respawning checkpoints or enemies that can spot you out of nowhere. Far Cry 3 takes what was bad about Far Cry 2 out, improves on what it did right, and then sprinkles some komodo dragons and magic mushrooms on top.The plot starts with you, Jason Brody, and your fellow spoiled-white-kid friends getting captured by Vaas Montenegro, leader of the pirates on the unnamed island you have decided to visit. After escaping, you set out to save your friends, and get off the island. While your character, and the slice of the 1% that you came to the island with, are often insufferable, virtually every other character is fantastic. Vaas is a psychopath, and absolutely drips of crazy; Dr. Earndhart is fantastically creepy; and Willis Huntley may very well be my favourite character of 2012.But there’s far more to Far Cry 3 than the story. It’s set in an open world, letting you wander off and ignore the plot completely in favour of hunting animals, taking outposts and climbing radio towers if you’d like. There’s a crafting system, allowing you to upgrade how many guns you can have on hand, how many syringes you can carry, etc. You’ll get most of the upgrades quickly, though, since there’s plenty of animals to hunt and skin, and while the final upgrades for most things are part of hunting sidequests that unlock at conquered outposts, they’re all available on the first island. There’s also a skill system, giving you new abilities and upgrades. XP is easy to come by, but some skills are locked behind missions and won’t be available until a ways into the game.While the gameplay is a lot of fun, I was sometimes left wanting more. The one downside to having outposts not respawn is that you can clear out an entire island of enemies and then have nothing left to do but hunt cassowaries and mop up sidequests. If you’re lucky you’ll run across the occasional firefight between a washed up group of pirates and your native allies, but those are often over before you figure out where the gunfire is coming from.Side missions are a mixed bag, all of them are fun the first few times, but they rarely stray from their formula. Assassination missions make you kill a guy with a knife, supply drop missions make you drive through some checkpoints, et cetera. Fortunately the hunting missions have at least some variety in what kind of weapons and animals you are using or going after. Using an RPG to hunt down a pack of rabid dogs is a lot of fun, I assure you.While there is a finite limit to the content, it’s not like this is a short game. There’s PLENTY to do in the story missions alone, and if you add general island dicking around time to that you have a very substantial experience. Even the formulaic side missions are good for a change of scenery every few hours.Speaking of scenery, this game looks good. Really goddamn good. and getting a very smooth frame rate with some amazing visuals. The first island is mostly jungles, but there are plenty of beaches, rivers, bunkers and so on and so forth. The game is also really colourful. In a world if grey and brown shooters, it’s great to see a game set on a tropical island that feels, well, tropical. There are bright birds and plants everywhere, and with the wildlife system the game world feels alive."
