,Recommended,220240,16048061,"Posted: 28 May, 2015",all,MerlinPants,"The great:  The pure sense of freedom.  Other open-world games plop in what they call a ""sandbox"", only to do what a parent would do to a kid in an actual sandbox, which is hold their hand and forcefully steer them to where they need to go and to what tools they need to use.  Far Cry 3 pushes the parent away, shoots them a few times, and spits on their remains.  When liberating an outpost, do you get points off for doing it stealthily?  Nope.  Do you get points off if you then get noticed and proceed to rocket-launch the place to smithereens?  Nope.  Do you get points off when you then throw a molotov at the empty shacks and burn it all to the ground?  Nope once again.  This game knows how to do things;  gives you a toolbox, and sets you at a task.  You can get anywhere on the map any way you want, you can kill animals any way you want, you can desecrate ancient tombs any way you want!  This leads to a ton of replayibility, natural variety, and emergent gameplay.The good:  The world.  While some areas can feel samey, (it's a lot of jungle), this in no way takes from the beautiful and artfully crafted environments.  The map is enormous, pocketed with hidden tombs and abandoned army bases, the lore is rich, as seen in carvings, scrolls, etc., and the forest around you feels alive and evolving.  While driving around, you could see a pack of wild dogs attacking enemies, or a jaguar hunting some wild pigs.  If you're sniping from a hill in the distance, it's entirely possible you will get mauled by a nearby tiger.  Additionally, the fast-travel system is not too intrusive and makes you work for it, as you must first liberate strongholds at varying difficulties.  All-in-all, the whole thing feels real.The bad:  Uplay and PC optimization.  Blah blah, Ubisoft sucks, blah blah.  Moving on from that, the only hang-up I have with this game is how it performs.  I can run a modern game like Dying LIght or Shadow of Mordor at about 45-55 FPS easily.  I cannot, however, manage to keep a steady 35 FPS in this game with a mid-range GPU.  I feel like there could have definitely been more optimization in regards to this platform, and as a result, my fan chugging away takes me right out of the experience.Other notable things:  The story/characters.  While the story isn't a twisty-turny masterpiece of fiction, it is written and acted out well.  The villains are charismatic and memorable (especially Vaas), the voice acting is pleasant, and the progression of events moves along briskly and with some intense set pieces.  I haven't yet played a mission where I felt bored, it's genuinely surprising.Result:  Buy it at no less than 25% off."
