76561198047366198,Recommended,220240,12294376,"Posted: 29 September, 2014",all,Rettznom,Far Cry 3 might be one of the best singleplayer shooters I have ever played. The action is great and you can have fun running and gunning your way through your enemies or take the sneaky approach stabbing them in the back and chaining together multiple enemies to take down at once. It is loads of fun and highly replayable. I'd recommend this to anyone.
,Recommended,220240,13601664,"Posted: 25 December, 2014",all,Theta-i,"Wow. I was blown away. This is simply an amazing title! I have played this for well over 200 hours and have enjoyed every single one. The game is solid in almost all aspects and feels like the sleek, open world, modern first person shooter that it is.Gameplay is solid and fun. It has a traditional feel to it. Guns do the right amount of damage, movement is smooth, and engagements with enemies feel fluent. It’s modern, that’s all there ist to say. The combat gives a strong ""Call of Duty single player"" vibe, but that's not a bad thing. Shooting an enemy with a lot of health causes them to flinch and drop their weapon, among other things. The enemies react to your movements and are not bullet sponges. When stealthing, enemies react very well to what you do. They notice dead bodies and more. For an open world game it's nice to see combat mechanics that are still up there and on par with games today. I'm looking at you Fallout.Combat 9/10The main story is where you will be spending most of your time, though, so that’s what matters. You’re Jason Brody, who’s stranded on an island controlled by pirates. The pirates have captured your friends, and over the course of the game your goal is to get your friends back and kill the pirate leader. The story has approximately 40 missions, but because of how they’re structured, it feels like a lot more. The story is divided up into unofficial “sagas” as I’ve dubbed them, where each saga deals with Jason dealing with one character. Halfway through the game a whole new game world is opened up with a whole new faction to fight. It refreshes things greatly.Story 10/10The game is open world and playable without exiting the game world (except for loading missions.) This is a great feeling, and even better if you’re not used to that gameplay like me. Being able to go from mission to mission exploring the island with minimal interruptions is great. Rook Island’s scenery is beautiful and there are many places to explore. Throughout the map there are radio towers to climb and outposts to liberate. The outposts can get slightly repetitive, but are very fun to liberate. After you complete the story, you can reset the outposts back to under enemy control. There are several ways to tackle an outpost and take it down, so there’s bound to be one to suit your style. The world lacks many targets of opportunity and special quests to do, and the existing ones get repetitive. However, on my first few playthroughs, it never crossed my mind- I was fully immersed. Only after playing Far Cry 4 I realized how it was lacking.World 9/10You’re required to make a Uplay account to play this game. It’s annoying and stupid, but you have to do that to launch the game. I made my account with a throwaway email adress, set it to auto sign in, and have had no problems since. Not as big of a nightmare as some think. The visuals are great, and compete with games today. Weapon models are detailed and look very real. Not much else is to say, the game looks stunning, but not overly detailed. Performance is solid, I have not encountered any stuttering with my GTX 760. However, at least for me, this game has had some quirks. Very rarely (only happened handful of times) parts of the map won’t load, weapon skins are white, and the map glitches. It’s not very common, but can be annoying. It doesn’t run in that aspect as smooth as, let’s say, an iOS interface, but it’s more than fine. The issues I’ve encountered are low in number and not game breaking.Performance: 8/10This is a simply stunning first person shooter. I recommend it to anybody who likes modern FPS games and is looking to switch up their library. Once you get past the Ubisoft DRM nightmare, it’s smooth sailing. I have played through the story over 5 times now and still love it. Great combat, graphics that hold up today, and a gripping story make this game a favorite in my book. Do not hesitate to buy this game.9/10"
,Recommended,220240,8384977,"Posted: 28 December, 2013",all,Mushy,"This game is pretty good. The freedom presented players is refreshing in today's shooter landscape but the lack of visual diversity (especially when compared to FC2) as well as  a less interesting tone than its predecessor. An interesting and brave concept and central idea is also pretty much ruined by hammy writing and voice acting. The game shines when it simply lets you loose on the massive (and gorgeous) world, the campaign missions are pretty restirictive but everythign else simply gives a group of enemies and a large and (most importantly) player driven number ways to tackle them. Shooting feels great, interface works well and this is one of the few genuinely good Ubisoft PC ports.Depending on your tolerance for repitition I'd say wait until this on sale to pick it up, but pick it up none the less"
76561198060107110,Recommended,220240,13698067,"Posted: 29 December, 2014",all,Verlaine,"I rarely play these kind of big budget, AAA games, but I saw this on sale and decided to gave it a whirl. I'm glad I did.The game is a wild ride, with a large variety of over-the-top vehicles, gadgets & weaponry at your disposal. The voice acting and dialogue are first grade, comparable to what you'd get in a first-rate action film.The combat and stealth are implemented quite well, despite an overreliance on QuickTime events. Those QT events make the game feel very ""console"" at times. Veteran gamers will know what I mean. It's hard to really *lose* here.The story is compelling and well told, despite the protagonist being a typical Joe Sixpack American-type. The villains are some of the most outrageous and cruelly entertaining I've ever seen in any video game. There are also some brilliant sections simulating drug-induced hallucinations that reveal a great depth of creativity.Be warned, you have very little control over the plot of the game. The only real chance to influence the plot comes at the game's very end.Highly recommended, if you can get past the highly scripted nature of the game and ignore its clear console origins."
