,Recommended,220240,14094070,"Posted: 21 January, 2015",all,chairbender,"Took me about 13.5 hours to beat. Fun mix of action and stealth. The game changes it up and managed to stay interesting even when I was spending extra time with sidequests / taking outposts. First person perspective is a nice change for an open world game for me and I enjoyed the precise shooting mechanics and the customizability of the weapons.One major complaint is audio fidelity. The audio quality of the voice over is just terrible coming from playing other open world games (like Sleeping Dogs). It's hard to describe, but it just sounds fuzzy and overall unpleasant to hear.I'm not going to complain about the writing, despite a lot of contrived and unrealistic situations and character behavior - I actually thought it was interesting overall and just wanted to keep playing to see what happened, but I didn't really feel that immersed by it. There's a lot of plot holes and things like that that don't really matter overall - the story is just a device to give you a bit more of a reason to enjoy the core gameplay. It does that fine and does so in an interesting way that made me feel like there was more thought put into it and more to get out of it (in terms of analyzing the deeper meaning of it) than I got from my initial playthrough.If you like open world games, I think you'll definitely like this. There's lots of activities to do, but, unlike in other games, I felt like I could be powerful enough only spending a small amount of time going out of my way to accomplish them. It doesn't feel overwhelming, but if you want to keep playing after experiencing the main story, there's plenty to do. The movement, geometry, overall area design, and traversal mechanics could've done a lot to harm the open-ness of the game, but I never really got frustrated with things like trying to climb hills or find a good route to sneak around to take over an outpost. The game rewards you with a surprising amount of power as you acquire new guns and skills, but you'll probably feel like you've hit the upper limit about 2/3rds into the game.If you like FPS games, you'll probably enjoy the variety of guns and quick, satisfying gunplay. Playing on a mouse and keyboard, I found it fun even though most encounters were easily overcome by pulling off headshots. As the game progresses, they change up the enemies in ways that keep the challenge consistent with your skills as you get more experienced with the mechanics."
