,Recommended,220240,14880977,"Posted: 14 March, 2015",all,Sam Houston,"Where FC2 makes you feel like a terrible person through amplifying gameplay, FC3 tries to do this through the narrative. Most of the complaints I've heard about this game come to this exact aspect (the aspect that makes the game for me): even when taking missions, you're not a good person. Your character is a massive♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥living out his action movie dreams, ""saving"" the natives from their oppressor. You're not supposed to feel good after completing the narrative, you're supposed to be left troubled and wondering. That being said, a couple of missions (mainly involving Buck) take this a little too far for me. There's a fine line between forcing players to question themselves about what they are willing to do to progress the game (a question asked many times throughout the story), and trivializing certain actions. FC3 doesn't always walk on the right side of that line, but for the most part it shows a good effort.My main complaints with this game revolve around the huge power creep. Whereas in FC2 at the end of the game you'll have better weapons but still need to play smart, by FC3's midpoint your protagonist has turned into God. You'll have access to items that literally make your character invincible, and while that's convenient for some of the more obnoxious quicktime boss fights, that's a cover for poor game design.There also is a good amount of extraneous features and systems. Hunting, crafting, WWII letters, Relics, plant gathering, radio tower, drug notes, etc. all seem fresh at first but quickly become tiring.  It's a troubling turn when the gamer views a ""secret"" marker on the map as another objective to be ticked off rather than a secret to discover, and FC3 goes far beyond that point. Some of the systems seem to have beem put together by dfiferent teams who never spoke with each other. After hunting an animal you can skin it and craft items with its skin. However, the animation for skinning is actually the protagonist pulling out the animal's internal organs and putting them in a bag. At first I thought this might be commentary on Brody's action hero fantasies, but after watching the animation for the 200th time I didn't care anymore.Coop is present but takes out all that makes FC3 different and fun. Whereas attacking a point in the Singleplayer game would allow a great deal of creativity. Coop is a linear shooter. Most levels have one specific ""best weapon"" and punish you tremendously for not using it. This is unfortunate, because between levels you use your experience to upgrade certain skills and weapons. If you specialize yourself in the sniper class and weapons, then you'll be entirely out of luck when you run into a level set in a cave or bunker. It can be fun to play with a friend or two, but Coop's definitely not the strong point of FC3."
