76561198085171447,Recommended,220240,23411384,"Posted: 5 June, 2016",all,dogboat333,"2012 was a good year for gaming in my eyes. Games like Telltale's The Walking Dead, Max Payne 3, and Mass Effect 3 were released, all of them are, in my humble opinion, some of the best games ever made. Sure there were some flops in there, *cough* Steel Batallion *cough**cough*, but for the most part the year was great. There is one game, however, that stands out from the rest in my eyes. That game is Far Cry 3, developed by Ubisoft Montreal and published by Ubisoft, this game was the first I playyed out of the whole lot and was the first game that I actually like that I had on my 360. After three years since my last play of the game, I remembered that I had this game on my Steam list and decided to try it again and see if it held up. So did it? Let's take a look.STORY: You're Jason Brody, a California rich boy who goes on an Asian tour with his brothers, his girlfriend, and his friends, culminating to a skydiving trip to the Rook Islands. Unfortunately, the Rook Islands is the base of a slavery ring, and you and your friends are kidnapped by pirates. You and your brother Grant escape where you're held, however he is killed by the leader, Vaas, and you barely escape, waking up to see one of the residents of the island giving you a tatau, a tribal tatoo that signals a great warrior, and they tell you that since you managed to escape, this signals the beginning of a change of the war. You have never killed a single person in your life, but you are the only person who is able to save your friends, so you have to go out and save them. The story is pretty good, it sounds like a silly action movie plot, but it goes a lot deeper than at times than some people might realize, as you see Jason turn from a ♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥♥ frat boy to a depraved warrior who might not be killing just to save his friends anymore. The story kind of loses steam in the second half when you run into a new villain, but for the most part its momentum keeps up. It has one of the best FPS stories out there.GAMEPLAY: First person shooter. You got a variety of weapons to go with and, as a result, a lot of ways to go at the game. Shotguns, LMG's, sniper rifles, if you want to go loud and proud or quiet or some mix of the way, you can do that, and with upgrades, you can carry up to four guns. There are two ways to upgrade yourself, one way is crafting, where you kill varying animals around the island to craft their skins into upgrades like weapons holsters and ammo pouches. This is fine, it's a bit annoying that you can't use any animal skins for them, but from a mechanical standpoint I do understand why they did that. The second way to upgrade yourself is a skill path that you get points for when you level up. You have three paths you can gain skills in, and you can go down any of these paths and get the bonuses in anyway you want, with a few restrictions so you don't get OP skills too early on in the game. This is also fine enough, there are some useless abilities in there, but that will always be the case with stuff like this. Overall, the gameplay is great. The gunplay is good and movement works fine.GRAPHICS AND PERFORMANCE: Ran at mostly Ultra settings, 1440p, above 60FPS constantly. Get a more recent graphics card like a GTX 900 or 1000 series and you'll be good pretty much. The game looks pretty good, and while it does show its age a bit in some regards, it looks really good overall.CHARACTERS, VOICE ACTING, AND DESIGN: Jason is not your usual silent protagonist, he actually speaks a bit, which is nice. His friends are finely voice acted and look unique enough. The villain for the first half of the game, Vaas, is honest to got one of the best video game characters ever. Later on the island you run into more colorful figures, from a CIA agent to a German privateer, you'll run into at least one character you like.SIDE ACTIVITIES: Outside of the story mission, there is a decent variety of things to do. The aformentioned hunting is fun, there's a lot of different animals to look for, from sharks to goats to bears. Across the island there are radio towers, which are platforming puzzles that, once you reach the top, you get a piece of the map revealed as well as some free weapons, which are nice to do. There are outposts across the islands on the island run by the pirates that, once you take over them, removes nearby pirates from the area and also gives you hunting missions and killing missions, all of which are fine. There are also little collectibles across the map; ancient relics, drug cards, and World War 2 soldier letters, which honestly feel kind of grindy to go after and collect. For the most part, though, the side activities are decent and don't get in the way of things.MULTIPLAYER: Oh yeah, multiplayer... didn't really play it, even on Xbox. I did play a bit of the co-op mode, which was alright I guess, but not really something to write home about. Ah well, though.FINAL THOUGHTS: One of my favorite games of all time, really. 10/10, there are some problems surely, but every game has them, and the game completely shadows them.. If the game interests you, pick it up when it goes on sale for sure.Have I ever told you the definition of insanity?"
