,Recommended,220240,16938127,"Posted: 7 July, 2015",all,CIA,"This game is easily one of the (if not THE) greatest single-player FPSes I've ever played. (There is multiplayer, but you don't need to know that. Seriously, don't bother.)Everything falls just right in this game; hunting animals to craft larger rucksacks, wallets and ammo pouches is fun (complete with certain equipment that can't be crafted without sidequest-specific animal hides), shooting feels just inaccurate enough with assault rifles, explosions feel explosiony, fire is gorgeous, water is gorgeous, and there are SO MANY WAYS to take on enemy outposts (from brute force, to range, to stealth, and even sneaky trap-setting).However, one detail sets this game apart for me:The sound.I don't mean the music, or the way footsteps fall, or any bitrate magic; I mean a very specific thing:Echoes.You see, when a gun fires, someone shouts, a car accelerates, or an animal roars and you are at a distance, a magical echoing effect is applied to the sounds, and there's something whimsical to hearing it. Allow an example:You're bearing down on your targets, safe in a cliffside. They have no clue a sniper is looking down on them. You shoot, and one falls without notice. Another. Another. But maybe you miss, or shoot the fourth guy in the leg, or someone turns around and sees his body fall down. Suddenly the outpost is in panic, men scream and shout, firing their guns at things that aren't there. Then one spots you, and you hear his call of ""I SEE ONE!"" ring out across the air. All this sounds cool, but as I said before, hearing it with echoes is truly somethingelse.Oh but Uplay is taped on to the game.9.99/10 - The rating level I reserve for Far Cry 3 because it is a perfect game that is hindered slightly by Uplay."
