,Recommended,220240,7906804,"Posted: 3 December, 2013",all,REDWOOD,"I'm a little far behind on the times, but I made good use of 10 bucks this earlier this week to buy the discounted deluxe edition of Far Cry 3 while it was on the awesome Steam sale. I'll be upfront, I never played any of the Far Cry series before. Most of my FPS experience came from Halo, COD, Bioshock, Borderlands, pretty much most mainstream FPS titles.I had read the reviews and saw about everyone saying the same thing: ""this map is huge"" ... and that's no lie. I've put 25 hours into this game already and I have less than half of the map exposed. Let alone grabbing the trinkets that lie along the way.This game has a feel from some of the bigger games on the market. There are towers to open parts of the map, much like what was in Assassin's Creed. The map is massively open world, something that could be seen in the newest GTA. The side quests are never ending, and there's an element of Mass Effect for you. You're not limited to two weapons and 4 grenades like is seen in Halo, which is welcome.But what may be the coolest part of it all is how much it operates like something you may expect in a jungle. Items are crafted by hunting in the jungles. Animals behave like wild animals. Bears hunt deer, wild dogs attack, buffalo rampage, and even birds can be shot down. Experience is gained and perks are awarded the more you gain experience. But while the map is massive (and I mean, it is MASSIVE), it doesn't feel like it oversteps itself. The world blends in very nicely, graphic detail is spot on. One of my favorite perks is seeing cars and people move around on the map, regardless of where I am. I could be on a mountain on one side of the island, look through my sniper scope, and see action happening on the other side. It gives it a more lifelike feel, something that's tremendously well done in my opinion. There's no more of that annoying, slgith blip that you would find when a car or a person loads on the map on the other side of the door. It's already there.This is a game that you could easily launch 60, even 80+ hours in and still never finish it. But each item that you pick up (these could be relic, letters, etc) you gain additional experience, so while it's nice to have that 100% completion at the end of the game, you constantly are gaining experience and getting strong for each thing that you do. In fact, the only thing you won't gain experience from is walking or driving around. Shooting a simple deer gives you XP.Beyond that, there are also outposts in the map that you can take over from the pirates and give back to the native people.While I'm nowhere near beating this game, I haven't been so drawn into a game in I'm not sure how long. It certainly is a game worth getting, whether you've played the series before or not. It's a fantastic FPS game, with great storylines and great acting as well."
