,Recommended,220240,11409325,"Posted: 25 July, 2014",all,c5,"Far Cry 3 is a great game and an example of how a sequel should be. While Far Cry 2 had good ideas and was even brilliant in places, I oftentimes found myself bored with it. Far Cry 3 takes what was good about Far Cry 2 and expands on it, while cutting out or seriously improving on the stuff that didn't work.Gameplaywise, the initial setup looks a great deal like Far Cry 2, dropping you into a gorgeous open world and letting you go about story objectives and side missions in whatever way you want to. The missions are mostly very open and generally give you a great deal of freedom. If you want to go into something guns blazing, you can do that. If you want to sneak around and take out everyone unseen, you can do that as well. Oftentimes attempts at stealth will go awry, turning everything into a chaotic rush to either get out of the situation or find some way to defeat the enemies with what you have. The battles are dynamic and the emergent gameplay this game has is wonderful. This was great in Far Cry 2 and it's great in Far Cry 3. One issue with Far Cry 2 is that everytime you completed a mission, you literally had to drive back to the center of the map to get the next one. This was extremely boring and led you to traverse the same areas of the map over and over again. Far Cry 3 alleviates this by giving you the location of your next mission as soon as you finish the previous one, which gives a nice feeling of progress and keeps you moving through areas of the island you haven't seen yet. It also allows for a fast travel option, which allows you to go to any friendly outpost you've been to before, which greatly expedites things. Furthermore, if you clear an outpost, the enemies stay dead, as opposed to Far Cry 2 where enemies would respawn (meaning you would have to fight the same battle many times). Side missions in Far Cry 2 were repetitive and unrewarding, but the sidemissions in Far Cry 3 have much more variety and give you a real sense of progress. Also, the guns feel much better this time around. In Far Cry 2, the weapons felt weak and unsatisfying, but in 3 they pack a real punch. Far Cry 3 has an RPG style levelling system that lets you upgrade your skills (including getting new melee attacks), and it's very enjoyable to level up and discover new abilities.In terms of storyline, this game is miles above its predecessor. Far Cry 2 wanted to tell a raw, gritty story of war in an impoverished land, but forgot to make you care, and more or less forgot to have a storyline five minutes after the intro. Both sides of whatever conflict was going on were basically identical and the game didn't give you any reason to care about one or the other, and none of the characters were given any kind of personality or storyline. Furthermore, the villain had no sense of presence and you had no reason to want to go after him, other than that it was your job. Far Cry 3 on the other hand, blows its predecessor's story out of the water. Right off the bat, you are introduced to Vaas, a human traficker who has kidnapped you and your friends. Vaas is one of the most memorable villains I've seen in a game, and is brought to life wonderfully through a combination of brilliant voice acting and incredibly natural animation. His presence permeates through the game and he imposes a real sense of menace on the world. The supporting cast is awesome as well, and you'll meet a wide variety of great characters. As you save your friends and become more accustomed to the world, the main character, Jason Brody, goes through an interesting progression, and it's fascinating to see how he develops through the game.Graphically, this game is gorgeous, and it performs very well. I have a GTX 780 (6gb vram edition), and on ultra settings, I usually got at minimum 40 FPS, although it was generally higher than that (at least when I ran fraps). Character models are extremely detailed and well animated. Foliage also looks great, and the lighting is brilliant as well. At times, the game looks almost pre-rendered. It truly is a nice looking game.Overall, Far Cry 3 is great. It improves on Far Cry 2 in every regard and gives you a ton of content for your money."
