,Recommended,220240,13014796,"Posted: 20 November, 2014",all,Yureina,"A bunch of pretentious 20-somethings go on a vacation to do ""cool"" stuff before suddenly getting captured by slavers on a South Pacific Island they had the misfortune of skydiving onto. Your character escapes and then goes off to try to free the rest of your merry band of friends.Since I'm already here, I'm going to start with story. Frankly, I found it to be the weakest part of the entire game. Having had basically no interaction with these people I am trying to save, I find it hard to care about them. I know the player character cares about them, but I, the player, have no reasons of my own. The other characters are a mixed bag of competence (Dennis, Sam), bleh (Citra, Volker), and above average (Jason, Vaas, Buck). And the only reason I put Buck up there is that he was the only villain that made me geniunely want to kill him. Sadly the game didnt let me choose how... :(So some poor character development in some areas, and then the plot makes some very abrupt shifts that made me either go ""WTF"" or just lose understanding of events. Partcularly at the game's ending missions and the final encounter with Vaas. They ended so quickly and rushed onto the next plot point that I was left scratching my head wondering if I had missed something. There are a number of story areas they could have done much better, but those two for sure.And if it wasn't for the gameplay, I'd probably throw this game off a bridge for making character/plot mistakes like that.But FC3 has gameplay, and much of it is pretty cool. One of the few open world sandboxes that feels truly ""alive"" as I came across countless unscripted encounters. Animals kill eachother, animals kill people, and... people kill other people quite alot. Being something of an animal lover (or at least someone who finds hurting animals distasteful), I was rather disturbed by the amount of animal killing that went on in this game. It made me sad to shoot playful dogs, beautiful tigers, or huggly bears throughout my entire time playing this. In fact, unless it was absolutely necessary ('this one is gonna kill me!' or 'I need animal stuffs to make this upgrade') I tried my best to leave the critters alone.There are also alot of different weapons, and you can carry 4 at a time when fully upgraded. You can also customize those weapons quite a bit to fit with your particular style. This ensures that you are able to play in the sandbox however you so choose. Do you prefer to go ""native"" with just a bow and a knife? Or to load up on silenced weaponry and take out entire outposts without them ever knowing you were there? Or are you the sort of person that handles life's problems with automatic weapons, flamethrowers, and rocket launchers? All of those will work, though sneakiness gives you more XP, as usual. Still, I had great fun playing like I was some kind of special forces commando, just as I did when I stormed in and either set everything on fire or just blew it up. Usually both.Anyway, its a big open world place with lots of stuff to mess with. Plenty to occupy ones time for a few dozen hours if not more. Fans of big sandbox games should feel right at home here. Sadly, I think the devs might have spent too much time getting their bears to be menacing and huggly, and too little time on developing characters and making a less failure of an ending.So... Yey for gameplay funtimes and sandbox adventures, but boo for story and (most) characters. Sadly I can only say ""yes"" or ""no"" on Steam rather than ""Maybe.""I'm going to choose yes because whatever failures the plot has is outweighed by the fact that this game allows me to just run around the jungles sniping people at one place and completely burning out the next. Yay!"
76561198077987627,Recommended,220240,28337596,"Posted: 12 December, 2016",all,Jonathan Taylor Thomas,"This game is amazing. If you want a FPS that is open world, this is a great one to jump into since there is a ton of nice gameplay and a good lot of things to do.Despite being a total blast, honestly, the story irks me in more ways than one.It swapped a ""save your friends and escape pirates"" thriller to become what the game truly is: Massacring evil pirates that deserve it in the most bad-*** ways possible.Not that the second part of that is even bad, it's just that the game blatantly lies to you about what it is when you jump into it. (Spoilers ahead, but as I said the story isn't worth much anyways).Let me give it to you this way. You are a socialite college kid on a trip with your best friends. You've never killed in your life. You worry about relationships and normal people things. You go to bars and party. You get kidnapped by pirates. These pirates scare you, keeping you for ransom, generally making you pee your pants. Not knowing what to do, your older military(?) brother leads you to an escape, and after the head ""I am de capitan naow"" kills your sibling, you get chased through the jungle while your flight instinct kicks into overdrive. You lose everything. You escape the prison camp, get rescued, and not even 2 seconds later you are leading a charge into an enemy outpost and gutting people with machetes. That's not an exaggeration, it's the next thing you do and the first thing you learn. Not even that long later, you find all of your conviniently alive friends... and then don't leave the island, because the game just switched antagonists and now you are psychotic warrior with a bloodlust. Talk about pacing.Had it just presented it like that from the beginning I still would have enjoyed the game, but it threw probably one of the most suspenseful taglines down the drain to become one of those games where you remove the criminal scum from a potentially nice place and save the values of the free world in the process.It's not boring, it's not a grind, but the story is a lie, and the character development of the protagonist from a college kid into a warlord is just putrid and rushed. And the worst part is that Vaas, that guy in the red tank on the cover - he's only your enemy for not even half of the game. Despite being a very believable crazy warlord character that is perfect for this flavor of game, he hardly lasts long. You know what I mean. Don't pretend you don't. And the guy they replace him with is just generic to the point of being laughable.There was so much potential with drawing out the ""saving your friends"" arch but most of your pals that you are lead to believe are important hardly have any lines or much of a personality beyond what you see in the first few hours. Had they just made it about your friends (and actually gave them character development) this might have been my favorite shooter. Like... they don't even help you. It's not even a team effort once you ""liberate"" everyone. That's how much they messed it up. You switch friends and the story continues on, with resident batman Jason Brozinsky, taking down all who share one of under 10 reused pirate models. Seriously. You go from some kid to Rambo in not even an hour after you finish the prologue. What are your friend's names again?So don't buy it for the story, instead, buy it for the beautiful map with a ton of lore, the fact that you can drop onto an enemy from the sky and then in one fell swoop take all of his buddies with him, and the fact that you can take down entire strongholds without being seen due to a great stealth system."
