,Recommended,220240,20292569,"Posted: 4 January, 2016",all,Mammoth Codpiece,"Edit (11/28/16): Nominated for ""Villain Most In Need Of A Hug"" AwardI give this game an 8/10. (Single-player only; I have not touched multi-player.)I disliked Far Cry 2 because it was repetitive and seemed like an exercise in futility--with entire enemy camps respawning in what seemed like no time. I stopped playing about 6 hours into Far Cry 2. But I read good reviews of Far Cry 3, bought it cheap a while back, and just recently played it. For a while, I thought it might be just more of the same.But I can tell you the exact moment I discovered I was having a hell-of-a-time playing Far Cry 3. for some reason, I had started liberating camps one by one from the pirates, usually by stealth with the sniper rifle, but sometimes by brute force. I came to this one small camp with about six guards fairly tightly bunched up in the yard. I stealthed up a ladder to the top of a building to take out the lone sniper that was covering the camp. How to take out the rest of the pirates? I noticed that there was a caged tiger in the camp. I could use that to even the odds a little against the other pirates, so I shot open the cage. Even if it killed one or two of them, that would make my job easier. I watched from my hiding place as the angry tiger took out one of the pirates. Then two. Then--holy crap--it took out a third as they were shooting at it. Then a fourth. That tiger managed to kill all the remaining pirates and liberate the camp for me! And lucky for me, he couldn't climb the ladder to my safe little hiding place. As I turned to watch the incoming Rakyat, to see if they would mop up that tiger for me--I felt myself being mauled in the back by an angry, wounded tiger! Unbeknownst to me there was, on the other side, a happy tiger STAIRWAY up to the top of the building I was perched upon. With only a shred of health left, I quickly turned and shot the tiger with the few remaining bullets in my clip. Lol. I will never forget that moment.So yeah, I fully enjoyed this game. Some high points were doing hunter quests to craft better bags, some of the intense combat set pieces, tomb-raider-esque puzzle solving, and, of course, sniping enemy camps. Stand-out performance by Michael Mando as Vaas. Negatives: The inventory system is crap. And towards the end I felt like I was accumulating lots of money with nothing really to buy. The story was totally implausible, and I despised the whiny rich white kid protagonist and his whiny rich white kid friends. Ugh. The Citra ending is pretty much what this kid deserves.Doubt I will be buying another Far Cry game since it looks like it's become a money grab with more-of-the-same. But I admit I enjoyed playing Far Cry 3."
