,Recommended,220240,9295900,"Posted: 28 February, 2014",all,The Counter of Strikes,"Fantastic game. So many great factors. Predators in the wild will sometimes inadvertently help you by jumping out from the jungle to attack enemies... or sometimes mess up your stealthy masterplan and cause you to alert the enemy to your presence when you're shooting a tiger in the face to get it off you, crocodiles blend in with the shallow water -- there's just so much. Hunting animals allows for upgrades, and picking up plants allows you to craft temporary buffs.The world is beautifully fleshed out and if you spend time doing the side quests/activities/item searching (there's a lot), you'll get a lot out of this game...Take the island over by climbing towers for map vision, and take out enemy camps for control.Many vehicles, flight suit, parachute -- there are plenty of ways to get around the jungle. Gain experience and build your tattoo (skill tree) for more efficient gameplay. The game also maintains a level of realism to try and keep you immersed in the atmosphere (switching around menus is a minor gripe, and not a major issue when you consider Far Cry 2 used in game menus)). -- The game does have a some cool ""Max Payne"" hallucination sequences using drugs as the machina. Also the game has some pretty cool temples which made me feel like Indiana Jones at times.So many weapons (which feel good to use), good AI, good difficulty, good story, good characters... a great all around game.I do recommend... you need to experience it for yourself since there's so much I left out. Although the game is fantastic, I'll say I hated the quick-time-event boss fights, but again, it's ignorable when you look at the game as a whole.Moments that stand out: setting a dock on fire by flamethrower-ing an enemy, then low on health needing to retreat from enemy fire... I go to jump into the water and notice 2 sharks circling.Not many games can scare/startle me anymore, but this game made me jump a couple of times (running away from angry cougar only to have a crocodile grab me in shallow water).Do get this game, worth every penny for entertainment value -- especially next time it's on sale."
,Recommended,220240,15014431,"Posted: 22 March, 2015",all,GRAU,"A visually stimulating world packed full of jaw dropping moments thanks to the incredible character acting and voice acting. You’ll never be left wanting from the moment you watch the first cut scene to the explosive final moments of your journey. The islands are teeming with enemy bases to commandeer, rare animals to hunt down and sights that will keep you enthralled for hours on end.You are tasked with playing the role of a young, extremely energetic man named Jason Brody. You find yourself and 6 of your family members/pals trapped on a fictional island called Rook Island which is situated near Papua New Guinea. The island is chock full of wild life, pirates, exotic plants, hidden caves, waterfalls and small villages to name just a few attractions. Rook Island is completely at your disposal pretty much from the get-go. It’s up to you to decide how you utilise it.Intense IntroFar Cry 3 begins with you and your friends having an awesome holiday together, frequenting bars, beaches, getting into fights and eventually being convinced to undertake the bright idea of skydiving. Accompanied by M.I.A.’s Paper Planes, you are shown a montage of the Brody Bunch & co. having fun and then hurtling through the skies in skydiving gear. Just as you think you’re about to see your group land, the footage you have just been watching is revealed to have been playing on a phone in front of your face. A young, sunken eyed, scar-faced man with a mohawk and red clothing is shown to be the one who has been dangling the video through the bars of your cage for your viewing. As Jason Brody, you look around the cage you have been confined to and see your older brother Grant tied up to one of the pieces of bamboo which structure the cage.He wears a nice smile, but deep down he’s twisted beyond repair.The foul mouthed pirate then goes on to give one of the best acted scenes in computer game history, forcefully instructing you and Grant that he’s the one in charge and that he’s planning on ransoming you for a handsome profit. After being called away by another pirate, you learn that your captor is named Vaas (superbly acted and voiced by Michael Mando). Vaas leaves you and Grant in your cage but Grant, having been in the US Army Reserves, proves his resourcefulness by escaping from his bonds and moving over to free your own hands.From here you both go on to make a daring escape through the pirate village and at the same time become acquainted with the controls of the game. Having reviewed Far Cry 3 on a PC I can say that the controls are as intuitive as you could hope.I won’t go on to reveal anything else that transpires during this introduction to one of the most awe-inspiring games you’ll have played, but I will go on to detail the features of Far Cry 3 that make it such an excellent experience.GameplayFar Cry 3 is littered with gun fights, vehicle races, treasure hunts and a plethora of other fun features that will keep you occupied for hours. To progress through the story line, you are presented with a yellow exclamation mark on your map indicating where to go or who to talk to in order to move on to the next part of the game’s wild adventure.For those who prefer to whiz through the game without looking back, you could easily finish Far Cry 3 in around 15 hours. For completionists you’ll be pleased to hear that there’s a generous provision of side missions to extend the game’s value past 30 hours. I personally took my time by enjoying every single moment and finished the game in 49 hours. It could easily have been more if I decided to collect every treasure, relic and get a high score in every trial.Speaking of side missions, you have many options to choose from…Scouting the LandRadio towers scatter the map that, when climbed and activated, reveal a section of the island on your in-game map. These towers can prove quite challenging to traverse and if you slip and fall, you will most likely die. But don’t worry, you just have to start again from the bottom of the tower. Treasure chests can often be found along your climb that award you with money, items and ammunition so keep your eyes peeled. Once you reach the top, the camera display will zoom out and show you places of interest that surround the towers and also unlock a section of your map to display the land and it’s secrets. You’ll also unlock certain weapons that can be freely acquired from vending machines when you scout the towers.Unifying Pirate CampsPirate camps are also littered around Rook Island, and as the name suggests are controlled by pirates. To appropriate these camps, you can go in guns ablaze or prefer to take a stealthy approach. The main goal is to leave no pirates standing. If you are seen, the pirates will become alert and can activate alarms which summon extra squadrons of pirates in vehicles to your location. You will need to eradicate every pirate in order to raise the flag of the native people to this land and wipe out the pirate presence. Rewards come in the form of extra XP by appropriating a camp without being seen, so stay out of sight of those pirates and keep it quiet.TreasuresIf you were to unlock the entire map without picking up any treasures, you will see just how many relics, chests and the like are waiting for your discovery. Treasures can be found around buildings, in amongst trees and rocks, underwater or in hidden caves to name just a few locations. They act as a way to earn extra XP, money or items to sell for monetary gains. Going on treasure hunts can be incredibly fun, especially if you have to dive down a great big hole in the earth into deep, dark waters. Climbing back out is the tricky part.ChallengesAll sorts of challenges await you on your travels throughout Rook Island. Courier missions will have you pilot a selected vehicle and pass through certain check points to reach the recipient in a set amount of time; Time Trials allow you to drive yet another selected vehicle and follow a path laid before you until you reach the finish line; mini-games such as darts, poker or shooting ranges and more. The massive amount of gameplay hidden throughout Far Cry 3 is astonishing and manages to keep you interested for a long time.Trials of the RakyatTrials of the Rakyat take the form of a small ‘instanced’ area where you are tasked with getting a high score by killing enemies with a provided weapon in a set amount of time. Large red rocks can be found throughout Rook Island that transport you to these trial areas. By activating these rocks, you will be shown the requirements of the specific trial and the points you need to get to attain a high score. Some of these are great fun, especially the one which gives you a car to squish pirate after pirate with.Side-MissionsAfter taking control of a pirate camp, a job board will become available. You can pick up hunting or assassination jobs from these boards. Hunting will task you with seeking out a particular animal and disposing of it using a certain weapon. Assassination jobs will require you to find a specific pirate and kill him with your knife. However you’ll need to stay hidden if you don’t want a fire-fight to erupt. Each side-mission will award you with XP and money, so make sure you get out there and earn that moolah!Read the full review"
76561197983419516,Recommended,220240,11906549,"Posted: 29 August, 2014",all,=ASJA= [WCK]Aimbot,"I just finished this game and I liked it a lot, but there were problems. Some were just annoying, like how when I climb a ledge, I am grabbing the air 6 inches away from the ledge or how if I got a phone call before getting a main mission, I'd have to hear it every time I loaded the game or completed a side mission.The best part was combat. The enemies in the first half of the game are easy to hide from until you start shooting. In the second half, they will see you better, but you are wearing their uniform so they won't be hostile until you are, or if you go into a restricted area. My only problem with combat was that if I miss with the bow, the enemies know where I was shooting from, but if you hit, they didn't seem to know. What made it great though is how the enemies rally and more will come once you start making noise. What seems like an easy fight against two enemies can quickly become a fight against 6, coming from different directions.This game fixes a problem I had with FarCry 2. In FC2, I was annoyed that to get anywhere easily, I had to drive through several outposts which were constantly manned by enemies that respawned rather quickly. There were not multiple sensible ways to get somewhere. Here, there are enemies around and you have to be careful, but there are choices, such as driving on or off road, or walking over hilly terrain. You also don't keep fighting enemies in the same spot every time. However, there is one big problem. There are these enemy controlled outposts throughout the island. They are avoidable, so they don't have the problem FarCry 2 had. However, while clearing them is fun, especially trying to go undetected, clearing the outpost makes the area ""safe"" meaning the tribe you are helping takes over. Now you will have allies in the area instead of enemies. The problem is that this makes those areas boring as there is no longer a threat. It also breaks my immersion. Where were all these fighters before? If the pirates have complete control of the island, why do they never take these outposts back?There is actually some story justification for why you go quickly from inexperienced and afraid to a killing machine. It may or may not be enough for you, but it's something.This was the first open world game I was able to stick with my attempt to not use fast travel. The world is big, but unless you are going from one end to the other, you don't feel like it takes forever. The island is beautiful and they really did great work and put in many detailed areas. The relics are meaningless collectibles, but they are worth collecting to see the locations where they are hidden. The Letters of the Lost, letters written by Japanese soldiers from WWII, were interesting and worth finding.Finally, most of the side missions were fun. The supply runs were a blast because they make you drive over crazy terrain, not just a road. The Wanted Dead missions were also cool and requiring a knife kill made several difficult. However, some of the hunting missions are stupid, such as when you are asked to ""hunt"" rapid dogs with an RPG or flamethrower. That's the Path of the Warrior?The main antagonist, Vaas was one of the best I've seen. They do a great job of exploring if your character is actually becoming like his enemy. However, they deal with him in a really stupid way. Basically, he beats you in cutscenes several times throughout the game. After one of these times, you go into what seems like a dream state where you fight him. You have no reason to think anything about it is real, but you wake up and are told Vaas is dead. That's it. Lame.Edit: The story justification is actually really good, but it is horribly unsatisfying from a gameplay perspective.The last problem is that the ending gives you a choice despite there being no choices to make during the course of the game. One seems to fit, but the other makes no sense and you have absolutely no reason to choose it. It's as if they tried to give you a Star Wars dark side option, or a choice like the original Fable. However because there were no morality choices throughout the game, it didn't fit. Also, something happens that made me want revenge. I have never wanted to storm an enemy camp and kick♥♥♥♥♥more than I did at he end of this game, but it didn't let me.Overall, I do recommend it. It was fun, but there are problems that keep it from being great. 7/10"
,Recommended,220240,23050121,"Posted: 17 May, 2016",all,CharlieLima79,"'Far Cry 3' is a very enjoyable open-world sandbox first-person shooter. Right off the bat, I was free to explore one of the two islands. I spent the first 16 hours of the game exploring, activating radio towers (the only time to date I actually enjoyed first-person platforming), hunting animals and relics, crafting bigger wallets and ammo bags, and -- the best part of the game -- liberating outposts. Given the dynamic game environment, each of my encounter or scenarios with enemies varied, and this made 'Far Cry 3' unpredictable and replayable.It wasn't until my 24th hour that I moved on with the story missions, which feature exciting set pieces and action. Just when I thought I've got the rhythm of the game down, the game granted me access to the second island. This second island features a different terrain, providing new challenges in liberating outposts and making me rethink my tactics. It's also full of nooks and cranies and secrets waiting to be discovered, just like on the first island.One of my very few gripes about 'Far Cry 3', however, was the boss battles. Like some of the contemporary action games I've played, boss battles were reduced to quick time events. This diminished the tension of the conflicts and made me feel more like an observer, resulting in rather unsatisfying gameplay. One particular boss battle was particularly disappointing because his character was already under developed; battling him by pressing a few buttons on cue made the experience even more underwhelming. This made me miss grand boss battles like those found in games like 'Crysis'Despite my annoyance about boss battles, 'Far Cry 3' remained entertaining and fresh as I approached my 50th hour into the game. The game has surprisingly much to offer. 'Far Cry 3' gets a very enthusiastic thumbs-up from me."
