,Recommended,220240,33591395,Posted: 16 July,all,Reanimate,"Far Cry 3 is an amazing game, and a game that I consider one of my favorites. Everything just works really well. The gameplay, story, setting, and characters mesh together nicely and form a unique tropical vacation that you will never forget!The story revolves around Jason Brody, a rich kid and daredevil who takes adrenaline rushing vacations numerous times a year. This time, you decide to go on a massive vacation with your other rich friends: a stock broker Keith, a champion swimmer Liza, a skilled pilot and your little brother Riley, a pot smoker and couch potato Oliver, and US Army veteran and your big brother Grant. While partying at a club, a man tells you about a skydiving excursion that he'll personally take you on, but you'll be blindly skydiving into an island that isn't certified. Despite denial among some people in the group, everyone agrees to it. What they didn't know is that they would be skydiving into an experience they would never forget, and I'm not talking about the skydiving part. Once they land on the island, all the friends are captured by pirates and are are used to try and get ransom money from the parents, then are thrown into a slavery ring. Jason Brody successfully escapes from one of these slavery camps. Now it is up to you to save all your other friends from imprisonment before they are sold into slavery by the main villains, Vass Montenegro and Hoyt Volker.PositivesBeautiful graphics.The graphics of Far Cry 3 look great, despite being an older game. They have aged well, and because of the age, the game is easy to run on NVIDIA cards on Ultra settings. My 960 could run this game at 1080p Ultra settings with no MSAA and stay at 55-60 FPS. I recently got my 980 Ti and I can run this game at 1080p Ultra with 8x MSAA, and I get a locked 60 FPS.Great story.The story of Far Cry 3 is great. It's insane in a good way, and you see Jason, along with other characters of the game, change and become new people as the story goes along, and you start to take a sort of side with the different people in the game. There's an important choice you have the make at the end of this game that this all leads to.Plenty of content.Along with the long and plentiful campaign, there's plenty of other side activities that you can partake in, such as Supply Drop missions, Wanted Dead quests, rare animal hunting, and collectible hunting!Awesome characters.All the characters in this game are likeable. All your friends are unique, and they're all neat people to get to know. Riley and Vaas were my two favorite characters in the game, especially Vaas. Vaas is probably one of the best villains you will ever come across in gaming. Despite some negative feedback, I liked Hoyt too. Some people say that Vaas should've been the only villain and he should've been in the game more, which I can agree with, but I didn't mind Hoyt that much at all.Vibrant and alive world.The setting of this game, the Rook Islands, is vibrant, alive, and completely awesome! It's a tropical/jungle island with tons of different animals inhabiting it, from bears, panthers, goat, tigers, sharks, deer, and many more, and these animals act like animals. Tigers will go after prey and attack them, and will also attack you if they see you. You can kill these animals for pelts that you can use to craft bigger pouches and holsters for stuff like ammo and grenades, and you can find rare animals through quests to get special pelts used to craft the best gear. There's different tombs and old WWII bunkers that you can explore to find collectables. There's two massive islands that the game is based around. There's what I call the Vaas Island, the one that inhabits pirates, and the Hoyt Island, the one that inhabits privateers. Both islands are great and varied in some ways. Vaas' island is dense tropical jungle, while Hoyt's island is more mountainous and void of almost any trees.Above-average selection of guns.From assault rifles to flamethrowers to bow and arrows, this game gives you an arsenal that you can use to save your friends, and you can do it your way! Will you sneak in with a bow and arrow and play a stealthy characters for more XP, or will you go in with a RPG and LMG and make as much noise as you can for the excitement and the fun? You get to choose your way!Plenty of multiplayer content.Along with the long campaign, there's also plenty of multiplayer content. There's a seperate co-op campaign with 4 unique characters seperate from the main campaign that you and 3 other friends can play through if you wish. There's a competitive multiplayer shoot-em-up counterpart that's kinda like CoD set in the Rook Islands. I'm not sure if people still play multiplayer a lot as I never got around to trying it, but from what I played back on the Xbox 360, it's pretty fun, and has some unique things that CoD doesn't have.NegativesBad performance on AMD cards.My RX 480, a card that is much better than the GTX 960, would get much worse performance. On 1080p Ultra, the RX 480 would get tons of dips into the 40s, while the 960 would stay at 55-60 FPS even during combat. It seems as if any AMD card runs this game like trash.Uplay.This game handles Uplay very poorly. There's two versions of this game: the base game and the deluxe edition. Problem is, once you buy the base game, you can't upgrade to the deluxe edition! If you want to upgrade the base game to the deluxe edition, you have to refund the base game and buy the deluxe edition, otherwise Steam treats the deluxe edition as another copy of Far Cry 3, so you can't buy it if you already own the base game. It was annoying, but at least I could fix the problem. This issue was fixed in Far Cry 4 where the DLC was on Steam as actual DLC instead of being one edition of the game.SummaryDespite any negatives this game might have, I still think Far Cry 3 is a great experience and one vacation everyone should take in their time of PC gaming. I love this game to death, and I'm glad it was my introduction into the Far Cry franchise.I wanted to throw in one tip right here. If you buy the deluxe edition, make sure you enter the key they give you in the game under Exclusive Content. I didn't do this until the very end of the game because I thought the content was already activated, but you have to activate the key in the main menu. Make sure to do it before you play as you get various early game bonuses."
