,Recommended,220240,7750583,"Posted: 25 November, 2013",all,Kinsmarck,"“Did I ever tell you the definition of insanity?”Gamers, if you’re fans of  first-person shooters or sandbox games, buy Far Cry 3. Buy it right now. Really, go ahead, I know Steam is open.  You're reading this on it right now.  I’ll wait.  Squared away?  Good.Allow me to start by saying that there's a very good reason for Far Cry 3 to be called the ""Skyrim of action games."" Ubisoft Montreal put together a blockbuster with this colorful descent into a surreal and bloody madness, departing refreshingly from the bland letdown that was the game’s predecessor.The game’s action elements are solid, boasting tight, well-polished shooting, simple and intuitive driving controls, and a suitably varied array of♥♥♥♥♥kickery available to players.  Its pseudo-RPG elements are also pleasantly deep for an FPS game.  The iterative augmentations to players’ melee and stealth abilities are particularly noteworthy, as each is often more brutally satisfying than the last, serving as fitting rewards for players, and as visceral illustrations of the main character's transformation from stranded adrenaline junkie to primal killing machine.  Each ability’s visual representation as a part of an increasingly intricate series of tattoos along Jason’s forearm is a nice touch of artistry and immersion as well.Between these abilities and Far Cry 3’s limited but effectual weapon customization options, it’s this potential for personalization that allows players to gradually carve out their own play style in Far Cry 3’s organic and flexible combat system.  One may select increasingly potent health boosts, and pack a shotgun and a fistful of grenades for wrecking pirate faces.  Another may opt for a more stealthy approach, relying instead upon knife takedowns, silenced guns, and environmental hazards to distract and dispatch enemies.Like bears.  In no other game may you make tactical bear-strikes.  Developers, get on this.  Now.An additional co-op mode, complete with its own story arc, alongside a fairly standard competitive multiplayer mode, keep Far Cry 3’s long-term entertainment value afloat, offering multiple gaming experiences under one digital roof.  That said, it’s worth noting that the game’s multiplayer modes don’t  allow for near the customization or freedom as that of the single player experience, though that’s to be more or less expected.  The gift that keeps on giving, however, is Far Cry 3’s admirably user-friendly map editor, which its player base has taken to creating some creative arenas with.Sadly, Pokerface Deathmatch is not one of them.On the technical end of things, Ubisoft obviously took their time with coding and QA testing this title. Even on mid-level gaming rigs, Far Cry 3 runs with admirable efficiency, and it’s a real treat on more powerful systems.  Even on consoles, the game is gorgeous in every aspect of its presentation, from its smooth graphics and diverse soundtrack, to say nothing of the actors’ stunning performances. Regarding the latter, my hat is way, way off to Michael Mando for his performance as Vaas, the game’s first and most memorable antagonist.The standout flaw of Far Cry 3 is that there simply isn’t enough of it.  The single-player story is rather short, ends abruptly, and doesn’t have much replay value.  Side missions will only last players so long, and once players clear regions of enemies, there’s no real sense that their victories are ever in jeopardy.  Once you’re finished with an area’s tasks, there’s just not much reason to go back. This, coupled with the patronizing hand-holding of the game’s map function keeps Far Cry 3 from really capitalizing on the dangerous wonder of its setting.In all, Far Cry 3 looks, feels, and plays like a startlingly entertaining amalgamation of standard FPS fare, Assassin’s Creed, and Skyrim, and damnit, I want more.Rating: 7.8Visuals: 9Audio: 8Controls & Mechanics: 7Atmosphere & Experience: 7Entertainment Value: 8For more reviews, articles, and videos, visit{LINK REMOVED}LastLevelPress.com!"
