76561198065481866,Not Recommended,220240,14797026,"Posted: 8 March, 2015",all,Onsilo,"Just putting my opinion into this for people who're looking into this game. My evaluation of this game would put it at a 6.5/10. I suppose all the hype and positive comments people had for this game raised had me expecting a crazy great game.The story wasn't all that great, despite people claiming it to be. The gameplay was alright, gunplay was solid as well as driving the vehicles which was probably the funnest part of the game for me.The enemy marker you have in game makes it really easy and takes the fun out of guessing where the enemies are. By spotting the enemies, they're highlighted orange and will highlight through every object that stands between you and them, meaning you basically have X-Ray vision. It takes almost no skill to kill enemies since you can always track them.The animations of looting and healing got tiresome pretty quickly.The side quests didn't really have any worthwhile incentives and taking into account that the game length was pretty long, there was quite a limited selection of weapons, not enough to satisfy my thirst for explosions and crazy spraying and praying. The selection of weapons was decent, but a lot of them I didn't bother using since I easily unlocked a higher tier weapon immediately after unlocking the lower tier ones.The crafting system is a joke, it works, but it's not really worth filling up your inventory space for.The leveling system is an even bigger joke, I don't even want to talk about it.You can go and attack enemy outposts to liberate the area which in turn allows you to do side missions that will unlock attachments for your weapons to be purchasable. Sounds great at first, but then you realize once a outpost is liberated the enemies disappear from that area immediately. No more encounters on the road, or in the jungle. All enemy activities cease from that area. And if you liberate all the outposts... Well, you no longer have anyone to fight.Once you beat the game you can go back to the island to continue exploring, however at this point there's not really anything worthwhile to do unless you want to convert this shooting game into a treasure hunting game, in which you look for the little totems of the indigenous people there and letters from Japanese soldiers of WW2. It's not worth the time, because you don't get anything out of it really.My biggest gripe about this game is that you never get to just outright kill the important foes. That and you wonder about how you got out of the precarious situations the villain puts you in, that would normally seal a mortal man's fate, (**SPOILER**-ish) only to get straight into a hallucinogenic knife fighting scene.You obviously have to win the fight to proceed through the game, but when you've killed the foe you wonder:""How the HELL did I get out of that situation!?"".(**SPOILER**) For example, getting stabbed squarely in the chest, (pretty sure to the heart), with a approximate 8"" blade, falling to the ground, blacking out, hallucinating a debate against yourself while walking down a magically appearing stone path, villain appearing at the end of the path and then knife fighting him, only to wake up in the tribal woman's lap who then declares you victorious for having killed the foe. You might, like I did, go on and say: ""What the F*ck!?"" ...For me the game was ruined by those strange inconsistencies and not being able to freely and outrightly killing my main antagonists. The exploration of the island was dull due to the fact that after clearing outposts no enemies were existent in the area, leaving my weapon almost useless aside from killing predators and critters.I wouldn't recommend this game unless it goes on a big discount or you have a lot of time to kill and excessive cash to discard, otherwise, not worth."
