76561198050301254,Not Recommended,220240,11543094,"Posted: 3 August, 2014",all,Cirno,"I bought the game because I'd heard it was ""like Skyrim but with guns."" This is true only to the extent that is an open world game where you aren't forced into the main storyline. The sidequests are uninteresting and minimal, and while searching the islands for treasures is interesting at first, the different items you find are all only worth as much as the money you sell them for. There is no crafting beyond leaves, so searching for trasures is ultimately useless unless you want to buy a new gun. The multitude of items is thus meaningless because you just end up clicking sell all in the shop anyway.Furthermore, whereas Skyrim let you play how you want, as a mage, assassin, brawler, etc, Far Cry is very limiting. Some missions require you to kill the final enemy with a knife. Hunting missions specify a bow, shotgun, or some other gun, limiting your ability to choose. Even the main storyline missions lack real choice, forcing you into dissapointing boss fights in which the only skill you need is how to move forward, literally, because you just have to walk to the cutscene where you kill the boss. I felt incredibly unsatisfied having killed a major enemy without ever needing to have done anything more than left a small weight on my w key.As for the storyline, without giving anything major away, you try to rescue your friends from pirates and use the island natives as a means to do so. I personally felt no attachment to my characters friends. Frankly, they seemed like a bunch of jerks. The problem arises when the other half, the Rakyat natives, is equally unappealing. The game didn't give me any reason to like them either, as they all just seem obsessed with a woman named Citra, a meant-to-be alluring, sexy ""goddess"" who just turned out strange and arrogant. With the two options presented to me, I honestly was left wishing I could join the pirates and make some cash on this island.Overall, I'd say this game fits a specific niche. If you like shooting things (except civilians, that kills you), this is probably a good game for you. If you like execution cutscenes, this is probably a good game for you (although the death from above is easily exploitable; any incline is enough to get the cutscene). If you're like me, and prefer an engaging storyline, personal playstyle, and/or any real reason to explore your open world, then you're likely to be disappointed."
76561198046348779,Recommended,220240,13311842,"Posted: 10 December, 2014",all,Terminal Thickness,Fantastic Game.
,Recommended,220240,11149202,"Posted: 9 July, 2014",all,jmbnbn,"Highly recommended - in my opinion this game manages to strike a great balance between open world and mission based, with a fun storyline and really enjoyable gameplay. Having been highly disappointed by FC2 I was a bit reluctant to invest in FC3, but aside from both being great looking games, they aren't really comparable.One thing I found particularly frustrating in FC2 was enemy outposts, which continually filled back up with enemies and made the game very repetitive. FC3 still has enemy outposts, but once won they remain yours and become fast travel points for you. Capturing these check points is also a really enjoyable piece of the gameplay, and you really can be varied in how you do this; sneak in and take out the alarms, killing guards by stealth. Or just go in gung-ho with a machine gun, blow up some stuff, then release a bear from a cage and let it maul the remaining guards.One thing FC3 gets a lot of stick for is its storyline, but my advise would be to just accept it for what it is without trying to see too much into it. It's a fun story line with some entertaining (if a little irrelevent) drug-induced interludes.This is one of few games where i'm quite happy to dip back in for an explore, paraglide around for a bit, or just drive around searching for enemy vehicles to blow up for a while."
