,Recommended,220240,10557452,"Posted: 20 June, 2014",all,Nitrocide,"Decided to update this review after I went through a phase of having absolutely no internet for nearly three weeks. It does things to a man, luckily for me my drive to do crazy was driven back by (not a wise choice of words, I'm aware) by this here game that I had installed prior to going through that so called 'phase'.Anyway, down to the actual evaluation. Turns out, given its release it's pretty easy going on the eyes, as in, the graphics are spot on. The next thing one notices in such a game are, obviously, the guns you get to handle. A rather small arsenal to choose from. Only 34 guns in the game in total. But the way you get to access them or finally get your hands on to them, I believe that should make it worth the effort.The vast choices and open world at your disposal make the game full of stuff to do long after you're done with the story. Although, pro tip; don't wait around for the story to end. Turns out you'd appreciate the things you unlock doing the misc. tasks prior to engaging in the main story. I tried the non pro way once. And then decided to finish the game once again, doing it this new way I call 'pro way' and it made the game a breeze. Only challenge I faced was because of the higher difficulty setting I put it on.If you're into crafting and therefore improving things by hunting and gathering crap spread across the gaming world, then you'd find this game your type as well. I'm personally really not into that at all. I usually prefer having better things awarded progressively by doing boring repititve tasks. (or so I think I do??)There's a huge, important, and carefully planned out stress on stealth in this game. One of the things that really attract my kind. I like it done in the dark with no witnesses, no survivors ;)Here's my old review to whoever actually bothered reading it and then had a panic attack realizing it had been changed! :""An extremely fun gun to play with friend